<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, Aug. 25, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Heads to Africa, Middle East
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is on his way to Africa to give
Nigeria's fragile democracy a boost and encourage efforts to maintain peace
among warring factions in Burundi. While in Nigeria, Clinton plans to tell
President Olusegun Obasanjo that the United States supports Nigeria as it
secures its democracy. He flew out shortly after the White House made known that
he is adding a Monday stop in Cairo to meet with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak, a Middle East ally, to discuss the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.N. Chief Releases Letter on Bomb
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan released a
controversial letter Friday which assured Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi that a
trial of two Libyan suspects in the 1988 bombing of a Pan Am jetliner would not
''be used to undermine the Libyan regime.'' The defense team for the two
Libyans, who have been on trial in the Netherlands since May 3, asked British
authorities to release the Feb. 17, 1999 letter from Annan to Gadhafi detailing
the terms of a trial under Scottish law. Libya accepted the terms and handed
over the two suspects seven weeks later.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Barks, Donald Duck Illustrator Dies
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GRANTS PASS, Ore. (AP) -- Carl Barks, the Disney illustrator credited with
giving Donald Duck his distinctive feisty and comical personality, died Friday
at the age of 99. He had been receiving chemotherapy for leukemia, but ''was
funny up to the end,'' said his caregiver, Serene Hunicke. Barks drew Donald
Duck for Walt Disney Studios from 1935 until 1942, and continued afterward as
the creative genius behind the Donald Duck universe.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Firefighters Battle Blazes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PROSSER, Wash. (AP) -- in an attempt to control a fast-moving wildfire that
had spread across 100,000 acres in two days, firefighters set backfires across
southern Washington's parched sagebrush country Friday. Sparked by lightning on
Wednesday, the fire was threatening 50 homes near the Yakama Nation reservation
and already had consumed 24 other structures. More than 5.84 million acres have
burned across the United States this year in what has been called the worst
western fire season in a half-century.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Badia Brand Paprika Recalled
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   Florida-based Badia Spices Inc. is recalling about 22,000 bottles of paprika
because the spice may be contaminated with salmonella, which can cause serious
infections in certain people. The Miami company recalled ''Badia Paprika'' that
has the following identification on the bottle's label: The expiration date
11-2002, and the UPC number 33844-00011. The paprika is sold in 2-ounce plastic
bottles. Consumers should not eat the recalled product but return it to the
place of purchase for a refund.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Experts Probing Gulf Air Crash
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) -- As Gulf Air Flight 072 approached Bahrain
International Airport for a landing Wednesday, pilot Ihsan Shakeeb requested a
''go around'' from air traffic controllers. Shakeeb, an experienced pilot,
circled Bahrain International Airport once, then aborted his landing attempt
without explanation, according to Gulf Air officials. Moments later, the Airbus
320 -- and its 143 passengers and crew -- disappeared from the radar and
nose-dived. U.S. and Bahraini teams are expected are meeting with six French
government experts and a representative of Airbus Industries to determine the
cause of the crash.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
FDA Warns of Bowel Treatment Effects
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A popular new treatment for irritable bowel syndrome could
cause severe intestinal side effects -- some requiring surgery -- that have
already affected at least 19 women. The Food and Drug Administration announced
Thursday it had ordered Glaxo Wellcome Inc. to attach to every bottle of
Lotronex a plain-English pamphlet explaining the risk, and that women should
stop taking it at the earliest sign of a problem. Women have reported either a
potentially life-threatening intestinal inflammation called ischemic colitis or
severe constipation, and the FDA has preliminary reports of another 14 cases
since Lotronex hit the market six months ago.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nasdaq Falls 11; Dow Ends Up 10
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks closed little changed Friday as traders, no longer
preoccupied with interest rates, searched in vain for guidance on the market's
direction. The Dow Jones industrial average ended up 9.89 points at 11,192.63.
On the NYSE, losers slightly led gainers. The Nasdaq was down 10.60 at 4,042.68
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mets Beat Diamondbacks 13-3
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Big Unit sure doesn't scare the New York Mets. Randy
Johnson again was sent to an early exit by the Mets, failing to strike out a
batter for the first time in 10 years as New York beat the Arizona Diamondbacks
13-3 Friday night. The Mets lead Arizona by 5&AMP;frac12; games in the wild card
race. The Diamondbacks have lost four in a row following a seven-game winning
streak.
AP NewsBrief by MARIA CODER 
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
	    
