<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Releases U.S. Poet  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN LEICESTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- Chinese police released the U.S.-based editor of
a dissident literary magazine after 16 days in custody and put him
on an airplane Saturday, sending him back to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Bei Ling, speaking by mobile phone on the way to Beijing's
airport, said Chinese and U.S. diplomats arranged his release to
smooth over ties before President Jiang Zemin travels to New York
next month for a U.N. summit and talks with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Police also freed Bei's brother, Huang Feng, late Friday, a
little more than a week after he was detained as part of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Bei's Aug. 11 arrest drew angry publicity in the United States
that threatened to undo months of diplomacy aimed at repairing
shaky U.S.-China ties. Well-known authors wrote essays demanding
his release that appeared in major U.S. newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Bei, a poet, has lived in the United States since 1988. Based in
Boston, he has edited a literary journal, Tendency, and he and
others have routinely smuggled copies of the journal into China for
distribution among Chinese intellectuals.
</P>
<P>
   While he has traveled back to China occasionally, Bei agreed to
leave the country as a condition for his release and it was
uncertain when he would be allowed to return. Police planned to put
him on an Air China flight bound for San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Bei said police accused him of illegal publishing and told him
if he refused U.S. exile he would face three to 10 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have to leave. I have no choice,'' Bei said at the departure
hall of Beijing's Capital Airport. ''If I didn't leave I would have
gone to jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Bei said he was not mistreated while he was detained, he had
eaten well and the prison was fairly clean. As part of his release,
police fined him $24,000, only $1,200 of which he was able to pay,
and they made him pay for his plane ticket to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   One of two plainclothes police officers who escorted Bei to the
airport said the poet was under a six-month parole while the
investigation continued.
</P>
<P>
   Bei's arrest came amid a broadening crackdown by the communist
government on the publishing industry. Chinese leaders fear that
criticisms of the government and calls for political change,
however mild, could further incite workers and farmers already
protesting corruption, layoffs, taxes and stagnating incomes.
</P>
</TEXT>
