<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Estonia Ferry Dive Prompts Outrage  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL TARM
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLINN, Estonia (AP) -- Ulo Veide can't focus on work this week.
His mind keeps wandering to a diving expedition seeking new clues
about why the ferry Estonia sank in 1994, killing 852 people --
including Veide's twin daughters.
</P>
<P>
   The Swedish and Estonian governments have criticized the
expedition as a desecration of an official resting place for the
750 bodies that were not recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ''They speak about disturbing the peace of the dead. But what
about the peace of the living?'' Veide asked. ''We deserve answers
to why our children died. It's about time there was an expedition
like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The ferry, en route from Tallinn to Stockholm, Sweden, went down
on Sept. 28, 1994, during a storm in the Baltic Sea off the coast
of Finland. It was one of Europe's worst maritime disasters.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about why it sank has included theories of
explosions and sabotage, despite a 1997 official report that blamed
poorly made bow door locks and criticized the crew for a slow
response.
</P>
<P>
   Veide, whose 24-year-old daughters Hannely and Hanka-Hannika
were at their first day of work on the ferry, doubts the official
explanation and welcomes the series of privately funded dives led
by New Mexico businessman Gregg Bemis.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a very traumatic week for anyone who lost loved ones
on Estonia,'' said Veide, a 62-year-old factory director in Parnu,
60 miles south of Tallinn. ''But I'm still glad it's happening. ...
I've been waiting for this for five years.''
</P>
<P>
   With Swedish and Finnish coast guard ships looking on, Bemis'
team of divers this week began inspecting the ferry, which lies
more than 250 feet deep. The divers have been going down in shifts
of six or seven at a time, the Baltic News Service reported.
</P>
<P>
   Finland, Sweden, Estonia, Denmark, Lithuania, Russia and Britain
have signed an agreement that declares the site an off-limits
sanctuary, but the dives can't be legally prevented because the
wreck lies in international waters.
</P>
<P>
   Bemis, 71, has said he will talk about what he found only after
the mission is over next week. His few public comments since the
dives started have hinted at discoveries but provided no details.
</P>
<P>
   He told Swedish officials he was searching for possible holes on
the starboard side of the ship and looking for charts on the
captain's bridge that might clarify the crew's actions.
</P>
<P>
   Bemis has said it was important to answer remaining questions
about the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no reason to believe that the technical investigation
we plan to go through with would disturb this resting place in any
way,'' he was quoted as saying by the Swedish news agency TT.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation by a Swedish-Estonian-Finnish commission, based
partly on more than 100 hours of underwater footage, blamed the
ferry's German builder, Meyer Werft, for poorly made bow door locks
and said the crew responded too slowly.
</P>
<P>
   A separate report, done on behalf of the German shipyard, blamed
poor maintenance of the locks and said a bomb could have exploded
on board, a possibility the commission dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors described scenes of horror on the 15,000-ton Estonia
as it sank, with seawater swirling up stairwells and slot machines
and tables crushing people as they slid across restaurants and
dance floors.
</P>
<P>
   Estonian Ander Paeorg, whose wife died in the disaster, said the
dive only brought bitter memories back to the fore.
</P>
<P>
   ''I see my wife in the eyes of my son every day, so of course I
can't forget,'' Paeorg said. ''But I have found a new rhythm in my
life, and so these kinds of events can be very hurtful.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics have questioned the motives for the dives. A German
television producer had a team on board to film them and reportedly
planned to sell the footage to television stations.
</P>
<P>
   Others said they didn't see what the dives could accomplish. The
Estonia is probably badly rusted, and may be covered in algae,
seaweed and silt, making it difficult to see or film the ship, said
Kari Lehtola, a Finn who was one of the official investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Some survivors say they don't know whom to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Risto Ojassaar, one of just 138 people who managed to escape,
said he hopes Bemis finds something that sheds light on the most
terrifying day of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I very much doubt he will,'' he said. ''I don't think we
will ever know what really happened.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
