<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House E-Mail Probe Upheld  </HEADLINE>
By GREG TOPPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A group that has dogged the Clinton
administration for months over thousands of missing e-mails will be
allowed to question the president's former top White House lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Judicial Watch, a Washington-based legal organization seeking to
unearth the e-mails, wants to question former White House counsel
Charles Ruff as well as John Podesta, President Clinton's chief of
staff, and attorney Virginia Apuzzo, the former assistant to the
president for management and administration.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Royce Lamberth said Friday he will hear
testimony in the case from Ruff on Monday. The judge did not say
whether Apuzzo would testify and said he would not decide whether
to ask for Podesta's testimony until he hears from Ruff.
</P>
<P>
   Lamberth said he hopes Ruff can say why administration officials
failed to tell the judge about a test of the White House e-mail
system conducted in 1998, four months after a problem was
discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Lamberth also denied on Friday a government request to end the
seven-month e-mail inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   A computer glitch in 1998 prevented thousands of messages from
being archived as they entered the White House computer system. As
a result, they were not reviewed by White House lawyers to
determine whether they should have been turned over to
investigators in cases including the Monica Lewinsky scandal,
Whitewater and campaign fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   The computer problems became public only last February, in a $90
million class-action suit filed by the conservative Judicial Watch,
which has filed several lawsuits against Clinton since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail investigation is part of a larger lawsuit over FBI
background files gathered in the White House on hundreds of
appointees from the Reagan and Bush administrations.
</P>
<P>
   Judicial Watch has accused White House officials of acting to
delay production of the e-mails until after November's election. It
has also said the administration has kept Lamberth uninformed about
progress in retrieving the lost e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Millet, a Justice Department attorney representing the
White House in the case, asked Lamberth to dismiss the e-mail
probe, saying any messages sought in other investigations already
have been handed over. He said there no evidence has been presented
that the government tried to deceive or lie to the judge.
</P>
<P>
   Millet, repeating testimony given previously in the case, said a
1998 test of the e-mail system wasn't reported to Lamberth because
of a ''disconnect'' between technicians and White House lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 and 1999, Millet said, the looming Y2K millennium
computer problem ''threatened to bring down everything'' and was a
bigger concern to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyer Mark Lindsay testified Wednesday that e-mails
lost in 1998 were the victims of a constantly crashing computer
system that was ''antiquated and unstable.'' He said the system was
upgraded in 1999 to head off expected Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay said he told Ruff and Podesta, then the deputy chief of
staff, about the e-mail glitch in June 1998 but never spoke to
Clinton about the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., chairman of the House Government Reform
Committee, criticized the Justice Department's efforts to end the
e-mail probe, saying government lawyers are ''looking for loopholes
to protect the president and vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   Judicial Watch general counsel Larry Klayman also asked to take
a deposition from first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton in the case but
has received no reply from the White House. Klayman said President
Clinton and the first lady, as well as Al Gore and his wife,
Tipper, wrote e-mail using pseudonyms.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said the Clintons have never had such accounts.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Gore said he has an e-mail account under a
different name for security purposes. It was not immediately clear
whether Mrs. Gore has such an account.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-26-00 0100 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000826.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Hopes To Emulate Fox Victory  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush is likening his
campaign to that of Mexican President-elect Vicente Fox, suggesting
a similarity of tactics and goals.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Fox did a good job of broadening the reach of his party,''
Bush told reporters after a meeting with the Mexican leader. ''He
challenged the status quo and presented a positive agenda.
</P>
<P>
   He made a compelling case that the status quo was not going to
be acceptable any more, Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that, if elected, he'll immediately seek a meeting
with Fox in November to demonstrate the importance he places on the
U.S.-Mexican relationship -- and dealings in general with Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, ''I've got to win first,'' Bush added.
</P>
<P>
   Fox will be inaugurated in December.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican presidential nominee was spending three days at
home and off the campaign trail before a three-day pre-Labor Day
trip to New Hampshire, Pennsylvania, Ohio and Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier on Friday, Bush spelled out his Latin American policy in
a speech in Miami, saying that as president ''I will look South,
not as an afterthought, but as a fundamental commitment of my
presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   He also pledged to breathe new life into stalled free-trade
negotiations with Latin America while keeping all current sanctions
on Fidel Castro's Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Bush then met with Fox, who has been touring the United States,
on the campus of the University of Texas at Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush congratulated Fox on ''a historic victory'' in winning the
presidency in July from the party that has run Mexico for more than
70 years. His election sends ''a strong signal of reform and
modernization in Mexico,'' the Texas governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that he, too, was waging a campaign ''against the
status quo.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I must do the same thing'' as Fox, he said, adding he was
offering Americans ''positive ideas'' and an opportunity to
''change the course.''
</P>
<P>
   He was less supportive of Fox's proposal that the United States
open its border with Mexico to allow unfettered movement between
the two countries of workers and goods.
</P>
<P>
   ''We discussed our borders. I made it very clear ... that we
will enforce the borders as long I'm the governor and if I'm the
president,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that enforcement would be ''in a humane way.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he agreed with the leader of ''our friendly neighbor to
the south'' that Mexican wages should become more competitive with
U.S. wages.
</P>
<P>
   As to open borders, ''I don't know whether it will work or not,
but I appreciate his optimistic vision,'' Bush said. ''When the
wage differential narrows, then perhaps it's a strategy we can
explore jointly.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he would request an increase in border agents
should he be elected -- primarily as a drug interdiction move.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's open-border proposal has also drawn skepticism from
President Clinton and Bush rival Al Gore, who met the Mexican
leader on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Fox told reporters after his meeting with Bush
that he hoped, ''We can build up a common future together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-26-00 0103 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
