<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 01:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bahrain Families Identify Victims  </HEADLINE>
By SUSAN SEVAREID
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) -- In small groups, relatives of the victims
of this week's Gulf Air crash began perhaps the most painful part
of their ordeal: identifying their loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   They started by looking at photos while seated at coffee tables
in a hotel meeting room under the eyes of medical teams and
counselors. Those who had been through it were easy to spot by
their blank stares.
</P>
<P>
   Nadr al-Khawaja, a Bahraini, helped his uncle identify a son,
daughter-in-law and their 9-month-old baby. The body of the
daughter-in-law, 19-year-old Marwa Badl, an Egyptian, was to be
flown to Cairo on Saturday for burial.
</P>
<P>
   ''We thank God that she was not destroyed like others,''
al-Khawaja said Friday. ''She was innocent, still young. She liked
to jog.''
</P>
<P>
   The uncle's son, Sultan Farja, and the baby, Mohammed, were
buried in Bahrain on Thursday, the day after the Airbus 320 crashed
into the Persian Gulf off the coast of Bahrain, killing all 143
passengers and crew members aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Photo identification was only the start, but Gulf Air
spokeswoman Alyson Evans said it was necessary to spare relatives
from having to walk past rows of corpses and body parts in a
mortuary. After the photo ID, relatives were taken to view the
remains for a final identification and claim them for burial.
</P>
<P>
   Officials did not allow journalists near the makeshift morgue in
a port near the crash site. It was not clear how many bodies had
been claimed, though many of the Bahraini victims were buried in
funerals Thursday and Friday. Several of the Egyptian victims were
expected to be flown to Cairo on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Evans said the medical teams on hand at the hotel were Gulf Air
staff trained to deal with the aftermath of aviation disasters.
</P>
<P>
   ''(Families) have dealt with probably everybody's worst
nightmare,'' she said. ''All we've tried to do is give them as much
comfort as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond psychological trauma, medical workers were treating
physical effects of the grief and had a room set aside where people
could lie down or receive medical care.
</P>
<P>
   Most people were being treated for hysteria, heart problems and
hypertension, said Sister Karima Inneg, a Gulf Air nurse.
</P>
<P>
   She was not sure how many people had been treated. ''So many,''
she said, shaking her head.
</P>
<P>
   While waiting, relatives quietly held each other and accepted
hugs and comforting words from airline staff -- many of whom had
lost friends among the plane's crew.
</P>
<P>
   Gulf Air said 135 passengers and eight crew members were on
board. Sixty-three passengers were Egyptian, 34 Bahraini, 12 Saudi
Arabian, nine Palestinian, six from the United Arab Emirates, three
Chinese, two British and one each from Canada, Oman, Kuwait, Sudan,
Australia and the United States. Two crew members were Bahrainis
with one each from Oman, the Philippines, Poland, India, Morocco
and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators from the U.S. National Transportation Safety
Board, French government experts and a representative of Airbus
Industries were to help determine the cause of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Airline officials said they were preparing to send the flight
data and voice cockpit recorders to either Europe or the United
States for analysis. A spokesman said it could take weeks before
the data is revealed.
</P>
<P>
   Sheik Abdel-Aziz Ahmed Nada of Al-Azhar University in Cairo,
mainstream Islam's most prestigious institution, conducted a
special prayer service at the hotel for about 100 relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ''You are crying, and it is a cry caused by separation,'' Nada
said as many relatives sobbed or buried their heads in their arms.
</P>
<P>
   ''Cry a cry of mercy. Cry a cry of separation. Cry like the
Prophet Mohammed, who cried for the loss of his son Ibrahim. Be
sad, but be sad out of mercy, out of the hurt of separation. Don't
be sad out of anger. Don't be sad in protest of God's will.''
</P>
<P>
   Nada, who arrived with the Egyptian relatives Thursday night,
described the victims as martyrs, a term traditionally reserved for
Muslims who die in holy war, but also used for victims of horrific
tragedy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
