<DOCNO> APW20000826.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Track Team Warned Of Drugs  </HEADLINE>
By BERT ROSENTHAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   COURAN COVE, Australia (AP) -- The first wave of
out-of-competition, no-notice Olympic drug testers has put the U.S.
track and field team on alert as the Sydney Games approach.
</P>
<P>
   While the team was working out on the Gold Coast on Wednesday,
10,000-meter runner Abdi Abdirahman was approached by
representatives of the Australian Sports Drug Agency to provide a
urine sample for testing.
</P>
<P>
   The agency and colleagues from Canada and Norway began drug
testing this week as part of the pregames testing of about 2,000
Olympic athletes, under the auspices of the World Anti-Doping
Agency (WADA).
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, the U.S. athletes at the team's training camp
on this resort island were warned about the protocol used by the
testers, which men's coach John Chaplin objected to in the case of
Abdirahman.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have no objections to the testing as long as they follow
the rules,'' said Chaplin, who has conducted drug tests for 15
years for the International Amateur Athletic Federation, the world
governing body of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they give us written authorization, show us who they are
and tell our medical people what they want, then we'll cooperate
immediately. They can't just walk out on the field and start
talking to people.
</P>
<P>
   ''For security reasons, we have to know who they are. They have
to identify themselves. The athletes have to know who they are so
they are valid.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Strand, one of the team's doctors, handed out drug
information and protocol procedures to the athletes, then addressed
the group in the dining room.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Australians are saying we're complaining about the
rules,'' Strand said, ''but it was the sloppy way in which they
approached things. We were unhappy with the selection process of
the athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ''Since then, we've had three conversations with the Australian
drug agency.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Australian Sports Drug Agency, Vicki
Kapernick, said the tester at the U.S. team's workout followed
proper procedures by going straight to the athlete.
</P>
<P>
   Kapernick said athletes can have a team representative accompany
them to the test, as Abdirahman did.
</P>
<P>
   That's what team manager Fred Newhouse stressed to the athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ''If a drug tester approaches you, you want to find an event
coach right away or Dr. Strand,'' Newhouse said. ''We have nothing
to hide. We just want it done right.''
</P>
<P>
   Strand concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are requesting the Australians to approach one of the team
doctors or a staff member so the process goes properly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chaplin said every American athlete had to be tested within 90
days of the Olympics or they couldn't come to camp.
</P>
<P>
   Kapernick said track and field was one of 27 international
federations that agreed to out-of-competition, no-notice testing
before the games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-26-00 0202 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
