<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Megawati Swears in Indonesia Cabinet  </HEADLINE>
By GEOFF SPENCER
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- In a sign of restored unity,
Indonesia's vice president swore in a new Cabinet on Saturday,
which embattled President Abdurrahman Wahid hopes will lift his
sagging political fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   At Wahid's request, Vice President Megawati Sukarnoputri
officiated at the ceremony at Jakarta's ornate state palace. He
attended, but was unable to read the oath of office because he is
almost blind.
</P>
<P>
   Megawati's participation was significant after days of feuding
over the composition of the 26-member Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   It also was her first official duty since Wahid bowed to
pressure from critics and conferred greater responsibilities on
her. A presidential decree defining her role was read at the start
of Saturday's ceremony, which was nationally televised.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Wahid nor Megawati talked about their recent differences
during the brief ceremony. Wahid said recently he would remain in
ultimate control of the government, saying Megawati has been given
new tasks, not new powers.
</P>
<P>
   Several ministers said they hoped the Cabinet could push forward
with reforms, following three decades of authoritarian rule under
ex-President Suharto, who is slated to face trial for corruption on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   New Economics Coordinating Minister Rizal Ramli said he had
spoken by telephone to Stanley Fischer, deputy head of the
International Monetary Fund, which is overseeing the restructuring
of Indonesia's crisis-ridden economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''The response from the IMF to the new Cabinet is very
positive,'' said Ramli, who has previously criticized IMF policies
toward Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   New Defense Minister Mahfud M.D. said he would continue to
pursue democratic reforms within the military.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Megawati, the daughter of Indonesia's founding
President Sukarno and a popular pro-democracy figure in her own
right, has been sidelined from the inner workings of the government
even though she leads the largest party in the national parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between Wahid and Megawati have been strained in
recent months as their fractious 10-month-old coalition government
failed to fix a deep economic crisis or end bloody sectarian and
separatist violence in several troubled provinces.
</P>
<P>
   Their differences came to a head Wednesday when she boycotted
Wahid's announcement of the new Cabinet lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Later her aides publicly criticized Wahid for stacking the new
Cabinet with his own supporters while excluding senior Megawati
backers from key positions.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid has defended his choice of ministers. He has said the new
ministerial team would be more professional than the 35-member
Cabinet he appointed last October when he became Indonesia's first
democratic leader in four decades.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-year-old president, weakened by a series of strokes,
promised to reshuffle his administration and enhance Megawati's
role after Indonesia's top assembly threatened to impeach him
earlier this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-26-00 0223 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
