<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 8 Survive Small Plane Crash  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HILO, Hawaii (AP) -- A small sightseeing plane with one of its
engines apparently on fire crashed into the Pacific Ocean. Eight
people were pulled safely from the water, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   A ninth person remained missing Friday night after rescuers
suspended their search because of darkness.
</P>
<P>
   The nine-seat Piper Navajo Chieftain was approaching Hilo
International Airport when the pilot said he was going to ditch it
in the ocean off Honoli'i Point, about four miles from the airport.
</P>
<P>
   The plane went down at least 200 yards from shore at about 5:30
p.m. Friday, the Hawaii County Fire Department said. The aircraft
belonged to the tour and charter company Big Island Air.
</P>
<P>
   Company owner Tom Beard said the flight originated from
Keahole-Kona International Airport, on the other side of Hawaii
Island, and was on a sightseeing tour of the island. He refused to
provide any other details.
</P>
<P>
   There were reports of burning fuel after the plane hit the
water. Another plane reported seeing five people in a life raft
before the wreckage sank in more than 100 feet of water.
</P>
<P>
   Four survivors were taken by helicopter to Hilo Medical Center,
while the other four were rescued by boat. The missing person was a
passenger, said Bruce Nelson, a spokesman for the Federal Aviation
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The eight survivors -- five men and three women -- all appeared to
be in satisfactory condition, hospital nursing supervisor Steve
Palmore said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It looks like everyone is going to be fine,'' Palmore said.
</P>
<P>
   A National Transportation Safety Board official was expected on
Hawaii Island on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The search for the ninth passenger was to resume Saturday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second plane crash involving Big Island Air within
the last year. On Sept. 25, a twin-engine sightseeing plane crashed
on the slopes of the Mauna Loa volcano, killing all 10 people on
board.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB has not ruled on the cause of that crash, but radar
data showed the pilot of that plane, also a Piper Navajo Chieftain,
was flying off the normal course used for sightseeing flights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-26-00 0224 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000826.0033 </DOCNO>
