<HEADLINE> Undersea Quake Rattles Sumatra  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Southwest Sumatra island was shaken
for a third time in three days when a magnitude 5.5 undersea
earthquake hit on Saturday, seismologists said.
</P>
<P>
   There were no immediate reports of casualties or damage, the
Indonesian Meteorology and Geophysics Agency said.
</P>
<P>
   The quake struck at 1:33 a.m. and was centered beneath the
Indian Ocean, 120 miles southwest of the town of Manna.
</P>
<P>
   A 5.2-magnitude quake hit the same area on Thursday and was
followed Friday by another with a magnitude of 4.8.
</P>
<P>
   On June 4, a 7.9-magnitude temblor killed at least 100 people
and left thousands homeless across the region, about 250 miles
northwest of the capital, Jakarta.
</P>
