<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schools complying with sprinkler law well before deadline  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Eight months after the fatal dormitory fire
that inspired the law, several New Jersey schools have installed
sprinkler systems in all rooms, beating the deadline by almost four
years.
</P>
<P>
   A fire in January killed three students and injured 62 others
Seton Hall University in South Orange.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later Gov. Christie Whitman signed a bill requiring
every dormitory room in the state to be covered by the automatic
firefighting systems.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the bill became law, Rutgers, Rowan University in
Glassboro, William Paterson University in Wayne and Seton Hall
announced plans to put fire sprinklers in all or some dorm rooms by
fall.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, William Paterson completed its $1.9 million project
and installed sprinklers at the 1,000-bed Towers dormitory - the
only residence hall that lacked sprinklers.
</P>
<P>
   The College of New Jersey and the New Jersey Institute of
Technology are nearly finished installation work on those campuses,
said E.J. Miranda, a spokesman for the state's Department of
Community Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Work at many of New Jersey's colleges and universities is being
done before state regulations are finalized. The state plans to
notify schools of the law's details sometime in November, Miranda
said.
</P>
<P>
   After the regulations are posted, schools then are required to
provide the state a work schedule, Miranda said. Until the plans
are forwarded, the state has no idea just how many of the estimated
53,260 dormitory beds are covered by sprinklers, the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once that's done, we will be able to keep track of where we
are and where we will be,'' Miranda explained
</P>
<P>
   But not all schools are able to install sprinklers immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Rider University needed to spend $1.6 million on improvements to
the water supply system in its Lawrenceville campus, said Tony
Campbell, the school's vice president for student affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ''In order to get the sprinklers in every room, we needed to do
the water system upgrades,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Rider is expected to begin sprinkler installation in the fall,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   That assumes the school can complete negotiations with
contractors and suppliers, a problem for several small schools, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   While the school waits to complete the sprinkler work, it has
taken steps to increase student safety, Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Each dorm room has a smoke detector hard-wired to the campus
security office, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The law gives schools four years to install sprinklers in every
room.
</P>
<P>
   The state also provided $90 million to help pay for the
sprinklers. Public and private colleges and universities would get
zero-interest loans, while boarding schools, military academies and
other schools that have dorms would have to repay the loans at 2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The bill allows exemptions for certain buildings. That would
most likely apply to ''very small'' buildings, state officials have
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
