<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Much-criticized charter school readies for new school year  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Following a first year plagued by academic
and disciplinary troubles, the New Covenant Charter School is
entering the new school year with a new management company, a new
curriculum and a new director.
</P>
<P>
   The problems of the Albany school affirmed the warnings of
critics who said last year it was too big and going too fast. Now,
New Covenant's new managers have one thought in mind: Get the
school reopened right after Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's the No. 1 focus,'' Director Eleanor Bartlett said.
''That's what I was hired for - to open this school.
</P>
<P>
   The school sent its amended charter to the State University
Board of Trustees just three weeks before its anticipated opening
date of Sept. 7. That document, totaling hundreds of pages, has to
be approved by the SUNY trustees and then sent to the state Board
of Regents, which can make comments or suggestions but not prevent
the school from opening.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how long the ratification process will take.
</P>
<P>
   As backup, New Covenant's former management company,
Boston-based Advantage Schools Inc., has agreed to subcontract the
new manager, Edison Schools Inc. so that the school could operate
under its old charter while waiting for the new version to be
approved. But SUNY officials maintained that the school will not be
able to reopen until the new charter is adopted.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's wait and see,'' said Connie Cullen, spokeswoman for
SUNY's Charter School Institute.
</P>
<P>
   New Covenant opened its doors in September 1999 as the largest
among the state's first three charter schools. Located in Albany's
predominantly black Arbor Hill neighborhood, just blocks from the
state Capitol, the school was also seen as a barometer by which
lawmakers could judge the charter school system.
</P>
<P>
   Charter schools are taxpayer-funded but operate with an
independent charter, or license, that spells out the school's
mission. They are offered as alternatives to parents dissatisfied
with traditional public school education.
</P>
<P>
   New Covenant's original charter was not finalized until
mid-August last year, when SUNY overrode the Board of Regent's
rejection of the charter and gave the go-ahead. Bartlett, a former
Regent who sat on the board that rejected the charter, acknowledged
that she questioned New Covenant's feasibility back then.
</P>
<P>
   ''The stability wasn't there. They had a new management company
coming in that had never worked in the state of New York,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   In its first year, New Covenant saw its student population drop
to 386 by June, well below the charter's projected goal of 550
students. In addition, 92 percent of the school's fourth graders
failed to meet the standards on the state's English test.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, the school's founder, Aaron Dare, first resigned
in June as the chairman of the board of trustees and then left the
board altogether in the wake of a state report alleging he
mishandled school funds.
</P>
<P>
   Separate critical reports released by the Charter School
Institute and the state Education Department this summer cited the
school's poor performance and management problems, as well as its
failure to create a permanent facility.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett said New Covenant's amended charter calls for the
switch from Advantage to Manhattan-based Edison and for the
problems stated in the reports to be corrected.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, school officials had said that the school's modular
classrooms were temporary and had promised that a new, 50,000
square-foot building would be erected by November 1999. The site
for the permanent building is still vacant.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Jack McEneny, an Albany Democrat, said New Covenant
officials were too ambitious and hurried in starting the school.
</P>
<P>
   ''You need to start small and experiment, see how it works and
then expand on merit,'' McEneny said. ''You need to downsize the
ego first. It requires a certain degree of humility, and I don't
see that happening.''
</P>
<P>
   McEneny pointed out that the school could have renovated two
former school buildings that are now vacant in Albany and expand
from there.
</P>
<P>
   Ward DeWitt, co-chairman of the New Covenant Board of Trustees,
said that option ''was not something we actively pursued'' and
countered that renovations are usually a ''bigger headache'' than
building a new school.
</P>
<P>
   Edison now has a new blueprint - a three-story model with each
floor housing an ''academy'' to create ''smaller schools within a
school,'' said Marshall Mitchell, vice president of development.
Under the Edison structure, New Covenant will be divided into three
academies: elementary (kindergarten through grade two), primary
(grades three through five) and junior (grades six through eight).
</P>
<P>
   Edison is finalizing the design and construction should begin by
November. The building is expected to be completed by August 2001,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company is still working on a financing plan for the new
facility. In the meantime, Edison is willing to draft a letter of
credit for New Covenant, Mitchell added.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have 79 schools in the country, so we do have some
experience in developing schools,'' Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   The school's target enrollment has been lowered to about 400, a
figure more in line with the limited capacity of the modular
classrooms, Bartlett said. This year, the school will enroll
students in grades K-six.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett has also met with Albany City School District
Superintendent Lonnie Palmer to discuss cooperative efforts, like
sharing lunch programs and custodial services.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer said New Covenant's approval last year came too late in
the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ''Financially, it was a big hit for the community,'' Palmer
said. ''We cut everything we could possibly cut, and we still ended
up borrowing $2 million from the state'' to make up for aid which
went to New Covenant and not the city's school district.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer said Bartlett's appointment and the switch to Edison are
''two hopeful signs'' that New Covenant is finally on the right
track. Before becoming a Regent, Bartlett had worked with Palmer as
deputy superintendent of the district.
</P>
<P>
   ''The downside is, they're just starting to work. The time frame
is even shorter (than last year),'' Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer estimates about nearly $4 million in public education aid
will be given to New Covenant this year if the school successfully
reopens.
</P>
<P>
   He said a shutdown of New Covenant will be a worse problem. The
district has used space vacated by students who went to New
Covenant to establish full-day kindergartens. The district is also
receiving federal aid by setting its class sizes at a set maximum.
If New Covenant students return, it could ''end up costing us a lot
of money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   New Covenant supporters are optimistic that it will not come to
that.
</P>
<P>
   ''Last year was a baseline. Now we know what we liked and what
we didn't like,'' said Seliatu Layeni, president of the New
Covenant's Parent-Teacher Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Accongio, principal and superintendent of the Charter
School of Science and Technology in Rochester, said the public
should give cut charter schools ''a little slack because they're
doing something monumental.''
</P>
<P>
   The Charter School of Science and Technology, which is also
managed by Edison, will become the largest charter school in New
York when it opens in September with 924 students in grades
kindergarten through eight.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 12 new charter schools are opening across New York
this fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
