<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 12:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Campaign designed to boost Advanced Placement participation  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The state's largest teachers' union has
entered into an alliance with the College Board to boost the
numbers of New York students taking Advanced Placement courses and
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Forty high school teachers received training this summer in
Advanced Placement English literature and calculus coursework under
the auspices of the College Board, the developers of AP materials
and tests, and the New York State United Teachers (NYSUT) union.
</P>
<P>
   The training is part of what the union said will be a
wide-ranging campaign to give more New York students, especially
those in inner cities and in rural areas, the opportunity to take
Advanced Placement courses. If students pass tests in various
subjects after taking the college-level course work in Advanced
Placement classes, they can qualify for college credits.
</P>
<P>
   ''The real winners will be the students in struggling districts
in rural and urban areas that have not been able to offer AP
courses,'' said Thomas Hobart, NYSUT's president. ''We are moving
closer to the goal of providing an opportunity for all students to
take challenging AP courses.''
</P>
<P>
   As things stand now, students in about three-quarters of New
York high schools can take at least one AP course. Last year, about
70,000 students in the state took one or more Advanced Placement
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Other aspects of the campaign to boost AP participation in New
York will be encouraging middle-school teachers to get students
involved in the College Board's pre-AP program and start bringing
course work in line earlier with AP courses students may face in
high school.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers do not receive extra money for AP courses, but many
like the challenge of teaching harder curriculum to what are
typically a school's better students, NYSUT spokeswoman Linda
Rosenblatt said.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the College Board, Gaston Caperton, said the
New York campaign will also address ''important equity'' issues.
</P>
<P>
   The College Board said it is trying to erase a disparity between
white and minority students who take one or more of the 32 Advanced
Placement tests it offers nationwide. Of some 700,000 students
taking tests last year, only 63,000 were Hispanic and 32,000 were
black. Black and Hispanic students make up nearly one-third of the
nation's public populations.
</P>
<P>
   The board, which has also faced charges of racial bias on the
SAT examinations it offers, says there is a disproportionately low
number of AP test-takers in inner city and rural districts.
</P>
<P>
   NYSUT said the state has also given the AP program a potential
boost by accepting grades of 3 of higher (on a scale of 1 to 5) on
the English, English literature and calculus tests as alternatives
to passing Regents tests offered in those subjects. The state Board
of Regents has started to phase in a new standard under which high
school students will have to pass five Regents examinations to get
a diploma.
</P>
<P>
   Low-income students in New York can qualify for aid to cover
part or all of the $77-per-test costs of AP examinations.
</P>
<P>
   But the AP system is not without its critics.
</P>
<P>
   In a study published this summer, Yale Professor Emeritus
William Lichten said the College Board misleads students by
promising that thousands of four-year colleges accept ''passing''
grades on AP tests for college credit.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Lichten said, something approaching half of American
colleges do not accept test scores of 3 as reflecting college-level
knowledge sufficient to earn college credit, and some of the most
exclusive schools have started not to accept 4s in some subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Lichten accused College Board administrators of being out of
touch with colleges by not recognizing that some institutions have
devalued AP tests and for not doing more to combat what he insists
is grade-inflation in the way AP tests are scored.
</P>
<P>
   The executive director of the AP program, Lee Jones, contended
that Lichten's research was flawed, as was his understanding of the
attitude of colleges toward AP exams.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he has been told flat-out by some administrators that
the decision to curtail the acceptance of AP tests for credit is
purely an economic one by colleges - they want the income from
students taking the credit hours instead of granting them ''free''
college credit.
</P>
<P>
   Accepting AP credit could mean a student would finish a degree
program in three or three-and-a-half years instead of four, thereby
''depriving a college of tuition dollars,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   AP tests are being graded the same way they have always been
graded, Jones said. The College Board believes a 5 score represents
a ''middle A'' under a college grading system, a 4 a ''middle B''
and a 3 a ''middle C.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It is possible that if a C at college is not what it used to
be, that that effects the AP's 3,'' Jones said. ''That is not a
problem with AP standards eroding. We match up our grading
standards to colleges, and I think that our process has help up
under scrutiny.''
</P>
<P>
   The State University of New York generally accepts 3s for
credit, though it varies with some campuses and some tests.
</P>
<P>
   While Lichten said New York students took the third-highest
number of AP tests per 100 high school graduates in the 1998-99
school year (62.4, behind Washington D.C.'s 83.7 and Utah's 63.5)
during the 1998-99 school year, New York was well back in the
middle of the pack when it came to how students did on the
examinations.
</P>
<P>
   Just over 64 percent got grades of 3 or higher, Lichten said and
35 percent scored 4s or better. Those were nearly identical to the
national averages but below the performances of students in most
other Northeastern states.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Lichten study: http://epaa.asu.edu/epaa/v8n29.html.
</P>
<P>
   College Board: www.collegeboard.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
