</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000826.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Programs cut, summer school expanded because of state tests  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER JORDAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - In New Rochelle, a praised eighth-grade
medical mentoring program was pared down. A handful of Erie County
schools recessed recess. And some teachers have dropped the curtain
on drama.
</P>
<P>
   The common denominator? New state Board of Regents-imposed
standards on students.
</P>
<P>
   A number of teachers and administrators say increasing pressure
to prepare students for statewide tests has squeezed out innovation
and time for breaks and play, drawing more students into summer
school for both remedial lessons and so-called enrichment
activities.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some of the things we used to do will be set on the side
burner,'' said Robert Hebert, principal of Cattaraugus Elementary
School in western New York. ''If you go back, there were individual
performances at each grade level. It is time-consuming with
students rehearsing all those lines. Hopefully we will get back to
something along those lines, but it will take time.''
</P>
<P>
   Cattaraugus this year for the first time offered a camplike
summer school for children heading into grades two through four. It
combined reading help with fairy tale performances. Hebert said the
standards were part of the reason for the program.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're becoming more and more jammed in the year with things
they have to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   New York is one of a number of states to place increasing
importance on statewide benchmarks. Fourth-grade students now face
English and math tests. Incoming 10th graders will have to pass
exams in English, math, global history and geography, U.S. history
and a science to graduate. The state's grading of schools depends
on how students perform, so tests are crucial to schools' public
images.
</P>
<P>
   ''The humanness of the students seemed brushed aside by the
pressure to raise the numbers,'' Sarah Carman, salutatorian of
Hudson Falls High School north of Albany, said in her commencement
speech earlier this year. ''It set up another wall separating us
from one another. Those who did well felt like geeks. Those who
didn't do well felt like idiots.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfie Kohn, a former teacher, author and critic of statewide
standards, has been working with teachers throughout the country
who oppose the standards.
</P>
<P>
   ''Teachers across New York state, especially the best teachers,
are finding it increasingly difficult to do the best kind of
instruction,'' said Kohn, who lives in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   He cited cutbacks in a mentoring program offered for the last
five years at Isaac E. Hayes Middle School. It put eighth graders
alongside physicians to interview patients and survey medical
literature.
</P>
<P>
   Before this year, the state allowed mentored students to get
biology credit. When Regents standards changed, the mentoring no
longer counted for biology even though the Education Department
acknowledges its success and says it covered much the same ground.
</P>
<P>
   Education spokesman Tom Dunn called it an overreaction to
criticize higher standards for the loss of the mentoring program.
''It's a great course,'' Dunn said. ''Why don't you offer it to
kids ... in the next grade?''
</P>
<P>
   But schools have to draw the line somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   At one of the Buffalo region's premiere school districts,
Williamsville, officials acknowledged last spring that they did not
comply with state regulations to provide daily exercise time
totaling 120 minutes a week. They said an already-packed schedule
and Regents efforts prevented it.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton-Fulton-Montgomery Board of Cooperative Education
Services' students in Johnstown are taking physical education
classes at technical schools because of schedule reshuffling due to
the new demands. Because BOCES centers lack fully-equipped gyms,
fitness walking or golf replaced volleyball matches.
</P>
<P>
   Summer school offers students the opportunity to make up some of
the fun activities. This year, 511 school districts and BOCES
centers offered summer classes, up from 406 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the state budgeted $35 million specifically
for summertime Regents preparation. And many schools are offering
summer school to younger students since fourth grade is ground zero
for the testing regimen.
</P>
<P>
   ''Regents' standards created summer school for these kids,''
said Irene Rosenthal, a fifth-grade reading teacher at Sand Creek
Middle School, outside Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Although a Regents defender, Rosenthal admits six weeks of
summer school - with classes of about 15 students compared to 25
during the school year - allows time for more creative incentives.
Her students this summer produced a newspaper based on the
Revolutionary War. And when they left book reports in paper
Christmas stockings, the next morning they found treats in place of
successful reports.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kelsey, 12, says he feels less afraid to ask questions
when there are fewer students in class and that he feels like he's
forgetting less by attending summer school.
</P>
<P>
   Not every student will get that opportunity, though, said David
Ernst, spokesman for the state School Boards Association.
</P>
<P>
   ''The state by no means covers all the costs of summer school,''
he said. So in poor or overloaded urban districts, that may not be
an option.
</P>
<P>
   Even without summer school, Kathy St. Laurent, a mother of four
in Minoa near Syracuse, is concerned about the amount of time
school takes from students' extracurricular lives.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd like to see them be a kid longer,'' she said. ''If kids
have all this homework, yet coaches still say they have to be there
Monday through Friday for practices, that's a lot. Not to mention
spending time with family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
