<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Bergen judge gets own TV show  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) - He once complained, ''I can live on a
judicial salary. I'm just not sure I want to die on one.''
</P>
<P>
   Now former Superior Court Judge Andrew P. Napolitano won't have
to worry about his paycheck. Starting Monday, the judge who once
held court in Bergen County will star in his own television show,
''Power Of Attorney.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many other court-based television shows, Napolitano's will
let ordinary people try their cases in front of millions on the
tube. But on this show, they'll get dream-team lawyers to argue
their cases for them.
</P>
<P>
   O.J. Simpson prosecutor Christopher Darden will represent a kid
who threw a rock at a BMW. Geoffrey Fieger, Jack Kevorkian's
lawyer, and Edward Masry, boss of the real-life Erin Brockovich,
will handle cases of wedding dresses ruined by seamstresses, and a
boy who says his father failed to give him the promised $25 for
every ''A'' on his report card. And F. Lee Bailey was involved in
the pilot episode.
</P>
<P>
   ''The lawyers are dramatic, dynamic,'' Napolitano told The
Record of Hackensack for Saturday's editions. ''They argue the
cases as if they were treason trials.''
</P>
<P>
   Napolitano knows the competition for viewers is cutthroat.
</P>
<P>
   ''I tell people they'd better get my autograph now because, by
Halloween, I might be history,'' he said. ''I'm not quitting my day
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Napolitano served at the Hackensack courthouse for eight years
beginning in 1987. Attorney Brian Neary, who faced Judge Napolitano
in Hackensack, believes the Napolitano's show will succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was a top trial judge,'' Neary said. ''He was very
hardworking and bright. He cared.''
</P>
<P>
   His show debuts Monday on Fox Channel 5 with two back-to-back
episodes at 9 and 9:30 a.m. Around the country, 208 stations --
covering 98.5 percent of the nation -- will carry ''Power of
Attorney.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, the Princeton and Notre Dame graduate became, at 36,
the youngest state judge ever appointed in New Jersey. He later
became the youngest to earn lifetime tenure.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to become a federal judge, but his nomination went
nowhere, and in 1995, he called a news conference to announce that
he was leaving. He complained about the pay and the lawyers who
showed up in court unprepared and sounding as if they got their
degrees from ''Fred's Barber College and Legal School.'' His
complaint about judicial salaries got so much attention that the
state's judges were awarded a raise just six months later.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the bench, Napolitano joined several law firms
before landing at Sills Cummis Radin Tischman Epstein &AMP; Gross in
Newark, where he handles cases involving corporate trade secrets
and disputes.
</P>
<P>
   He also became a legal analyst for several television stations
and has been a weekly commentator on the Fox News Channel since
1998. It was while on a Fox show that he was spotted by a
television producer in Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
