<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of birds infected with West Nile virus doubles  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The number of dead birds found to be
infected with the West Nile virus in New Jersey has doubled in the
past week to 322, according to state officials.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Riley, a spokeswoman for the state Department of Health
and Senior Services, said that the increase should not be cause for
concern.
</P>
<P>
   ''The birds are the most sensitive indicator of the virus
spreading, but there's definitely no reason to panic,'' she told
The Philadelphia Inquirer for Saturday's editions. ''We'll have to
see what happens in the next few weeks. What we've seen in other
counties is that it starts with a few birds, then snowballs after a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   Included among the 165 infected birds found last week is a crow
discovered on the campus of Princeton University - the first bird
found with the disease in Mercer County.
</P>
<P>
   Testing has continued across the Delaware River in Bucks County,
Pa., but officials there say so far no infected birds have been
found.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Southard, a spokeswoman for the state Department of
Environmental Protection, attributed the rise in West Nile cases to
the success of county surveillance programs and heavy rains at the
peak of the mosquito season.
</P>
<P>
   There have been no confirmed cases of humans infected with the
virus in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Humans can contract West Nile, which killed seven people in New
York last summer, only by being bitten by a mosquito that has fed
on an infected bird.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
