<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Learning dignity and civility, plus grammar and long division  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Susan Nadler has been teaching long enough
to remember the ''good citizenship'' lessons of the 1960s - and how
they got thrown out the window in the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had workshops on how to keep values out of the classroom,''
the Schenectady middle school teacher recalls of those latter
freewheeling days. ''You could not impart your values on anybody or
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Wait long enough and anything will come back in style.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Nadler and teachers across New York are under state
orders to teach things like tolerance, honesty, dignity and respect
for others to students at every grade level.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents say successful values education could lessen the
chances of Columbine-like violence in New York schools.
</P>
<P>
   By including the mandate for civility, citizenship and character
instruction in a broad school safety law signed by Gov. George
Pataki in July, New York joined the majority of states requiring
character education in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a quality of sadness about it in that, have we got to
a point where we have to mandate or legislate the teaching of what
we used to take for granted: civility and character,'' said Tony
McCann, a high school English teacher in the Shenendehowa Central
Schools in suburban Albany who, like his peers, has begun thinking
about how to meet the new goals.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we always recognized those things have to be taught,''
he said. ''I think the assumption in the past was those things
would be taught at home and reinforced at school.''
</P>
<P>
   But these days, after being horrified by school shootings in
Littleton, Colo.; Springfield, Ore.; Fayetteville, Tenn.;
Jonesboro, Ark., and Edinboro, Pa. - to name a partial list,
administrators are taking no chances.
</P>
<P>
   Tough gun laws are already on the books; they have not stopped
the violence. Educators hope to reach children before they even
think about picking up a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ''You start with this theory that, from the time the student
gets on the bus, we have consistent rules on what's expected,''
said Dennis Tracey, a high school teacher in the North Rockland
Central School District in Rockland County. ''If a student brings a
weapon to school, it's zero tolerance. If we have consistent
expectations in behavior all the way through, I think we'll have a
much better way of making this work.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Mary Donohue recommended New York adopt the civility
and character component after chairing a school safety task force
last year. It is one of 15 components in the Project SAVE (Safe
Schools Against Violence in Education) legislation, which also
gives teachers more authority to remove disruptive students from
the classroom and makes classroom assaults felonies.
</P>
<P>
   ''I taught from the late '60s to the '70s and as I traveled the
state chairing the task force, I noticed a distinctly different
atmosphere in the public schools,'' Donohue said. ''There was much
less emphasis on civility, on interaction, respect for individual
differences.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York State United Teachers documented the changes in a
1993 report, ''Conflict in the Classroom,'' which foresaw the
violence of recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ''New York state's classrooms are no longer immune to the
conflicts of the outside world,'' began the report, which cited the
need for enforceable behavior codes amid teachers' fears over
deteriorating student conduct.
</P>
<P>
   While the civility requirement amounts to another mandate at a
time when new performance standards have teachers under increasing
pressure, Donahue said it has been well-received across
philosophical and political lines.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how the values will be taught will be left to individual
districts, which will interweave them in the existing curriculum,
Donahue said, rather than ''as a separate civility 101.''
</P>
<P>
   Many New York districts already have successful programs in
place. Schenectady's ''Character Counts,'' for example, emphasizes
values of honesty and respect in the high school, while the North
Rockland district teaches the ''Three Rs,'' standing for rights,
responsibility and respect.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the end of the day, the practical effect is to ask
localities to avail themselves of the curriculum materials that are
already there,'' Regents Chancellor Carl Hayden said.
</P>
<P>
   Nadler, who teaches at Oneida Middle School, said a large part
of values education involves teaching by example.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you expect them to do homework, you should have the papers
corrected the next day,'' the 32-year veteran of classrooms said.
''It's how you treat them. Let them know how, in turn, they are to
treat you and how they should treat others.''
</P>
<P>
   Donahue said civics lessons can also be infused into discussions
of historical figures.
</P>
<P>
   ''We emphasize to our children what made them the individual
they were, not just the ostensible achievement they attained in
public and community service,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   There is agreement that it was not a sudden collapse in society
that led to the need for this mandate, rather a societal evolution.
</P>
<P>
   ''Kids are bombarded with so much stuff between the computers
and television, the songs they listen to, and there is a different
atmosphere out there,'' Nadler said. ''What I see is kids are more
worldly.''
</P>
<P>
   McCann spoke of a need for schools to be ''an island of culture
or respect and civility, even in a sea of chaos and rudeness.''
</P>
<P>
   ''But there is a tremendous question behind the whole thing,''
he added. ''Can the schools reverse what is happening in the
general culture or do they inevitably reflect to some degree what
is happening in the general culture?
</P>
<P>
   ''If kids are watching 'Jerry Springer' on mainstream television
or 'South Park' with its rudeness and crudeness, and they're
listening on the radio to shock jocks on a daily basis and we come
along and try to say to them, 'This is all wrong,' the school then
becomes a countercultural institution,'' he said, ''which we may
very well have to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-26-00 1321 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000826.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big stuff, big kids -- the struggle to fit it into classrooms  </HEADLINE>
By LYNN BREZOSKY
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLTON, N.Y. (AP) - Wall space spent, poems ''about me'' spill
out of a fifth-grade classroom and onto the hallways of Charlton
Heights Elementary School. There they bump up against the rolls of
construction paper that didn't fit into the storeroom.
</P>
<P>
   The faculty bathroom had some space, but it was taken by boxes
of computer paper, stacked against walls and under sinks.
</P>
<P>
   In a school built in 1958, Year 2000 learning just doesn't seem
to fit.
</P>
<P>
   ''Overall enrollment has not grown,'' said Christy Multer,
spokeswoman for the Burnt Hills-Ballston Lake school district. ''We
need more space because there are more things in the classroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's classroom is hands-on and high tech. That can mean
teepees, area rugs, story couches and math mommies sharing space
with computer stations and corner science labs. Inclusion has added
wheelchairs, computerized voice boards, oxygen tanks and individual
teaching aides.
</P>
<P>
   Books tend to be bigger, and so are book bags. Gone are the days
of five rows of desks and a front-and-center teacher's desk. Now,
desks are more likely grouped into topically based learning
stations with the teacher's desk shoved in a corner to double as
shelf space.
</P>
<P>
   Take Anne Long's kindergarten class. Twenty-five years ago,
Long's ''stuff'' was limited to dittos and workbooks. Now she has
counting games and big (18-by-24-inch) books that allow pupils to
track the printed words during story times. Children are broken
into groups to pursue different activities - such as learning on
the computer, and that takes space.
</P>
<P>
   ''Kindergarten is a microcosm of life, and these days life is
busy,'' Long said. There are even mock dishes in the mock kitchen
sink.
</P>
<P>
   Or Carol Douglas' fifth-grade room. The morning announcements
come into the classroom as an internal news show, presented on a
large TV that juts from the wall like a basketball hoop.
</P>
<P>
   There's a large abacus next to a large calculator, and a
''dramatic play area'' that's been a kitchen, a castle, a
restaurant and a hospital. The walls are covered with art projects.
</P>
<P>
   During the last 30 years, New York state has continued to revise
its minimum class size requirements from 550 square feet to 660
square feet to today's 770 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even houses and bedrooms are bigger - there's not anything
unique to schools,'' said Robert Rogers of the state Education
Department.
</P>
<P>
   But teachers say even bigger is still too small.
</P>
<P>
   ''You take two teachers and 22 children and put a nurse in there
with that bottle of oxygen and it gets very crowded,'' Long said.
</P>
<P>
   The average U.S. school is 42 years old, built during the
post-World War II years when births peaked at 4 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   Today, in the midst of the baby ''boomlet,'' a record 52 million
children are attending 88,223 schools. To accommodate this, the
nation is in the midst of a schools construction splurge that could
top $42 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, Joe Agron of American School &AMP; University Magazine
in Overland Park, Kan., said, is that average per-pupil space
allotment is in many cases getting more generous but classroom
space itself is staying the same.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one's really focusing on the classroom, which is probably a
mistake since the classroom is where most of the learning is going
on,'' Agron said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the International Council of Educational Facility
Planners in Scottsdale, Ariz., the modern classroom's biggest space
hog is the computer.
</P>
<P>
   ''For every computer you add to the elementary classroom, you
displace 1.5 students,'' said Debbie Moore, the council's director
of operations.
</P>
<P>
   And those students themselves are getting bigger. A growth trend
in children - taller, definitely wider - makes classroom furniture
seem Lilliputian.
</P>
<P>
   Passing a fifth-grade classroom, teacher Carol DiLallo pointed
out pupils who seemed to spill over their desks. ''When they stand
up, I think there's another adult in the room,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It's not universal, but American children as a whole are bigger
than they were in the days of the old Green's Corners School, a
19th-century one-room schoolhouse a few miles away from Charlton in
southern Saratoga County.
</P>
<P>
   Height researcher Richard Steckel has spent decades exploring
links between height and social environment, and says a strained
family environment or poor diet may prevent a child from reaching
optimum height. And the growth rate of the latest generation of
American children lags behind most Europeans, particularly the
Dutch. But as a whole, the population is continuing to get bigger,
he says, and where kids are tall, they may be heads taller than
their parents or grandparents were.
</P>
<P>
   ''Certainly fatness exceeds linear growth,'' said Leslie
Lieberman, a professor of anthropology and pediatrics at the
University of Florida at Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   Green's Corners makes this evident. Once the school fit 35
children and a potbellied stove within its 480 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Karis, the historian who maintains the old school, opens
it to tours for one month out of the year. A typical school group
numbers 18 to 28. ''I have to take them through in shifts,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-26-00 1328 </TRAILER>
