<HEADLINE> For USE SUN Aug. 27th and Thereafter  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
   1970:
</P>
<P>
   An elementary school built for 300 pupils:
</P>
<P>
   Large class sizes; basic room configurations and
classifications; very few, if any, special program requirements;
multipurpose room that serves as a gym, lunchroom, auditorium,
etc.; building provides 62 square feet per student.
</P>
<P>
   1983:
</P>
<P>
   The same elementary school originally built for 300 pupils:
</P>
<P>
   Fewer students enrolled in nation's schools; many buildings are
closing; newly available space allows smaller class sizes and new
program demands, such as computer rooms, expanded libraries, art
rooms, etc.
</P>
<P>
   1999:
</P>
<P>
   Expanded elementary school required for fewer than 300 students:
</P>
<P>
   Need for small class sizes, additional new program demands and
incorporation of technology, among other things, require major
retrofit and an addition to the original 1970s schoolhouse -
significantly increasing its size to accommodate similar number of
students. In addition, space provided per student grows to 105
square feet compared to 62 square feet in 1970. Still, educators
say there's not enough space, that schools are being asked to house
much more than in the past.
</P>
<P>
  SOURCE: American School and University Magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
