<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arbitration panel gives some union workers King holiday off  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WALLINGFORD, Conn. (AP) - A state arbitration panel says at
least some town workers should receive Martin Luther King Jr. Day
as a paid holiday next year.
</P>
<P>
   The panel on Friday awarded the paid holiday to 55 supervisors
who are members of the Connecticut Independent Labor Union.
</P>
<P>
   But their decision is not binding. The Wallingford Town Council
could still reject it, in which case the decision would be
forwarded to another arbitration panel, whose decision would be
final.
</P>
<P>
   Two other arbitration panels are still conducting hearings on
whether to give the holiday to other town workers.
</P>
<P>
   Wallingford is the only Connecticut municipality that does not
close its offices in honor of the January holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor William Dickinson Jr. has said he wants the town's six
unions to give up one of their existing 12 annual holidays to make
room for the King holiday.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy has led to allegations of racism and national
publicity, including a visit to town by the Rev. Jesse Jackson in
April. But Dickinson has held steadfastly to the position that the
issue is solely a labor problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature last year passed a law designed to force
Wallingford to settle the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The law called for mediation, followed by arbitration if the
mediation failed to resolve the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   In the town's last offer to the union, it proposed swapping
Lincoln's birthday with King Day, so workers could have King Day
off, and it proposed giving each worker an additional $50 per year.
</P>
<P>
   While awarding the holiday to workers, the panel also noted that
the town had negotiated in good faith.
</P>
<P>
   ''The record shows that the town and Mayor Dickinson long have
stood willing to provide MLK Day as a paid holiday,'' the
arbitration panel concluded. ''...the town (specifically Mayor
William Dickinson) has been inaccurately and unfairly pilloried by
public critics who have accused the town of harboring a peculiar
objection to MLK Day as a holiday.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson called the arbitration ruling ''wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Each of us wanted the same thing. So what has the town
received in return for a new day being granted? Nothing. It's a
gratuitous gift of a new day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A dissenting arbitration panel member, William F. Smith Jr.,
criticized the union for not fairly compensating the town and for
being interested not so much in honoring King, as in gaining
another day off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-26-00 1333 </TRAILER>
