<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Operator of Cape May-Lewes Ferry agrees to stop serving food  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOWER TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) - The operator of the Cape May-Lewes
Ferry agreed to stop serving prepared food this week after four of
the fleet's five ships failed a third round of health inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors at the U.S. Food and Drug Administration asked the
Delaware River and Bay Authority to stop food service last week,
saying in a letter that ''conditions under which food is stored,
handled, prepared and served remain unsanitary.''
</P>
<P>
   The FDA said the unsanitary conditions could pose a threat to
the health of passengers, a claim the authority denied. Federal
officials had threatened to get a court order to block food service
if the authority did not agree to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't fight City Hall,'' DRBA spokesman James Salmon told
The Press of Atlantic City for Saturday's editions. ''You fight it,
and you look bad in the press. You don't fight it, and you still
look bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon said the authority asked the FDA to give it until Tuesday
to shut down food operations. Most of the 162 full-time
food-service employees will be transferred to the terminals until
the ships are allowed to resume the service - a process that could
take at least three weeks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon said the authority will continue to sell prepackaged food
and plans to hire a full-time director of food protection, whose
job will be to ensure that the ferries are following correct
procedures for food service.
</P>
</TEXT>
