<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Education Sec. Takes School Tour  </HEADLINE>
By ANJETTA McQUEEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Shedding light on the plight and promise of
America's small-town schools, Education Secretary Richard Riley is
taking his annual ''big yellow bus'' tour to the banks of the
Mississippi River.
</P>
<P>
   As self-described ''city boy'' from Greenville, S.C., Riley says
he wants to focus on oft-overlooked rural education issues. But the
nation's top education policy-maker was to embark Sunday on a trip
that promises to goad the GOP-led Congress into passing the Clinton
administration's nationwide school-construction and teacher-hiring
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are the things that make a difference,'' Riley said in
an interview on Friday. ''They will eventually pass. If this
Congress is that shortsighted and does not make some of these good
surpluses we have, we will have missed a most important
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley, the longest-serving education secretary, will visit
schools in Mississippi, Louisiana, Arkansas and Tennessee in the
weeklong trip. Riley, also one of the longest-serving members of
Clinton cabinet, started the tours as an annual vehicle to
highlight national priorities and bring his message closer to
parents, teachers and children.
</P>
<P>
   He rides in a charter bus painted to look like a school bus.
Members of Congress, governors and mayors often hop on and off to
greet him when he arrives in their jurisdictions.
</P>
<P>
   Riley insisted this year's trip -- in the midst of a presidential
election year with both major candidates seizing the education
issue for votes -- is not a get-out-the vote effort for Vice
President Al Gore, the Democrat's nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is about citizenship, not partisanship,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Recently released figures show improvements in student
performance in math, and boosts among minority high-schoolers in
reading and minority middle-schoolers in science. But
overwhelmingly, by most federal and state measures, the nation's
poor children -- most of them black or Hispanic -- lag behind their
more affluent peers.
</P>
<P>
   Riley said that's what's bringing him to the Delta this week:
''Twenty-five percent of American students go to rural or
small-town schools. Schools are always at the center of building up
a community; that is especially true in the rural areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Riley will release a report detailing what's
needed to improve rural education. The report focuses on schools in
10 states in the Deep South, Appalachia and the Great Plains. These
schools, he said, suffer from declining enrollments, the lowest of
teacher salaries, crumbling buildings, pervasive poverty of
students, and poor housing stock that draws limited property tax
money for supplies and other needs.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:http://www.ed.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
