<HEADLINE> Probe widens to include deputies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NORWICH, Conn. (AP) - A state investigation into the county
sheriff system has expanded to include the financial and business
records of 50 deputy sheriffs across the state, according to a
published report.
</P>
<P>
   The probe by the attorney general's office had reportedly been
focused on the actions of the state's eight high sheriffs,
investigating possible violations of tax and gun laws. But Attorney
General Richard Blumenthal has issued new subpoenas that focus on
allegations that deputies misappropriated money from garnished
wages they were charged with collecting, the Norwich Bulletin
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It is being alleged that some deputies have deposited money in
their own interest-bearing accounts for a period of time before
turning the funds over to creditors. The deputies would then keep
the interest earned on those funds, the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
   The subpoenas are seeking all records pertaining to wage
executions and bank statements.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations are similar to those facing Windham High Sheriff
Thomas White.
</P>
<P>
   White faces embezzlement charges in connection with a check he
says he inadvertently deposited to a personal account rather than a
business account while serving as a deputy. The check was for
between $1,000 and $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   White, 38, has said he repaid that money with interest. He has
explained the deposit as a mistake he made because he was never
properly trained as a deputy sheriff when he was appointed in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Several deputies have challenged the subpoenas issued by
Blumenthal, as did four high sheriffs who were subpoenaed earlier
this year. A hearing is scheduled for Thursday in Middletown
Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   The expanded investigation comes as the high sheriffs are
gearing up for their campaign to defeat the proposed constitutional
amendment at the Nov. 7 election that would eliminate the office of
high sheriff. Should the amendment be approved, the deputies would
be placed under the oversight of the state's Judicial Branch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
