<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Drug Tested in Dominican Rep.  </HEADLINE>
By SUSANNAH A. NESMITH
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) -- American researchers
testing a new AIDS drug needed patients who had never received any
treatment. The Dominican Republic has them -- by the thousands.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems like a win-win,'' said Joy Schmitt, spokeswoman for
Agouron Pharmaceuticals of La Jolla, Calif. People ''are getting
treatment ... and we're getting the patients we need for the
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Agouron is using Dominicans to test its capravirine because it
can be hard in the United States and Europe to find patients who
haven't received any other treatments, between health insurance and
public health systems.
</P>
<P>
   Finding such people here was easy: More than 2 percent of the
country's 8 million people are infected with the AIDS virus -- and
few can afford medicines that cost many times the average income.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one helps you here if you have this disease,'' said Fe
Maria, who lived 13 years carrying the AIDS virus without hope of
getting treatment before going on the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Capravirine, which researchers hope will help fight off
mutations of the virus, has already been through the safety phase
of testing. In the current and critical phase, 90 Dominicans and
about 200 people in the United States and Canada are helping test
its effectiveness. Some participants get a four-drug cocktail
including capravirine; others receive a drug cocktail without
capravirine.
</P>
<P>
   Fe Maria, who asked that only her first name be used, has gained
weight and feels better, although the medicines give her headaches.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ellen Koenig, an American physician who has lived and worked
in the Dominican Republic for 31 years, was the impetus behind
bringing the trial here. And she insisted the company agree to
continue paying for treatment after the test.
</P>
<P>
   ''In some places, the drug companies come in, do the trial and
then they leave, and the people don't have the money to buy the
medicine,'' said Ceneyda Brito at the Dominican advocacy group AIDS
Action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-26-00 1408 </TRAILER>
