<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> RETRANSMITTING to add photo number  </HEADLINE>
By WAYNE PARRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH ORANGE, N.J. (AP) - When Alyssa Merla heads back to Seton
Hall to begin her sophomore year, she'll have the usual
back-to-school things on her mind: Will I like my dorm? How much
will textbooks cost? Which classes will be the toughest?
</P>
<P>
   But she'll have something else on her mind as well: the memory
of flames illuminating the dark hallway of her dorm; choking smoke
pouring into her room; waiting what seemed like an eternity for
rescuers to arrive; and deciding she and a friend had to brave the
smoke and run to safety or die in their room.
</P>
<P>
   Merla was one of hundreds of freshmen roused from sleep on the
morning of Jan. 19 when a fire broke out on the third floor of
Boland Hall, Seton Hall's on-campus housing for first-year
students. Three students were killed, and 62 others were injured.
</P>
<P>
   With a new school year set to begin this week at the state's
only Roman Catholic University, the cause of the blaze remains
undetermined, and rumors that as many as three students may have
started it continue to circulate. The Essex County Prosecutor's
Office will only say the fire remains under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But The Star-Ledger of Newark, citing unnamed sources, has
reported that investigators are focused on three Seton Hall
students who they believe either set the fire or know about it. The
newspaper reported that one of the students admitted vandalizing
the lounge where the fire originated, but not to setting the blaze.
The investigation stalled when the suspects stopped talking to
police, sources told the paper.
</P>
<P>
   That led police to stage a raid on a Newark bar popular with
Seton Hall students a month after the blaze, allegedly to crack
down on underage drinking. But lawyers for some of the 20 students
arrested said authorities issued subpoenas to a half-dozen students
wanted for questioning about the fire.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty and the lack of closure to a traumatic event
still weigh heavily on the minds of students who survived the
blaze. They may wonder: Is that guy next to me in literature class
a killer?
</P>
<P>
   ''That aspect of it can be scary, not knowing what caused it, if
it was one of my fellow students,'' said Nick Donato of Sparta, who
broke his wrist and ankle jumping from the third floor to escape
the flames. He still has to go for regular physical therapy. He has
sudden flashes of pain and walks with a slight limp.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he and others who survived the blaze are looking forward to
the new semester and have a generally upbeat attitude about their
sophomore year. They cite $4.5 million worth of sprinklers Seton
Hall installed in its dorms, a new awareness of fire safety, and
the support of others who've gone through what they experienced.
Freshmen move in on Thursday; classes begin on Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm very optimistic about school,'' said Merla, of West Long
Branch. ''The sprinklers are in, and I've got wonderful friends
that support me. There's no real fear of going back in anyone's
mind, but we're definitely all thinking of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Merla said not knowing what caused the fire is hard for Seton
Hall students.
</P>
<P>
   ''We basically don't know anything,'' she said. ''But I'm not
going to go into class thinking, 'He could have done it, or she
could have done it.' We're all trying to have a good feeling about
going back to school.''
</P>
<P>
   The fire broke out in a third-floor lounge before dawn, filling
the floor with smoke and sending hundreds of terrified freshmen
staggering into the cold outside.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, firefighters found the bodies of Frank Caltabilota of
West Long Branch, John Giunta of Vineland and Aaron Karol of Green
Brook. All were 18 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Merla said she waited in her room for a half hour for someone to
come rescue her.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought I was going to die,'' she said. ''Somehow, I made it
out of there. I went through my suitemate's room, and we made a run
for it. I opened up the door, and I saw flames, and smoke was
spilling in like crazy, so I closed the door.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were yelling up from the ground to put towels under the
door, that there were firemen on the floor coming to get us, but
nobody was,'' she said. ''We were all terrified. We didn't know
what to do. We figured if we stayed there, we were going to die, so
we ran out into the hall and made a run for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Donato came to the same conclusion and decided to jump for his
life.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was either that, or not make it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet all the students injured in the blaze who are medically able
to return to class will do so this fall, university spokeswoman
Shannon Allen said. None of those hurt in the blaze decided against
returning to Seton Hall, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The blaze cast a harsh spotlight on Seton Hall's fire safety
preparations. The university acknowledged that for years it didn't
hold organized fire drills as required by state codes, because it
believed that false alarms that resulted in evacuations counted as
the same thing. State investigators subsequently found hundreds of
fire safety violations at the campus, which Seton Hall says have
all been addressed.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen students, including the families of two of the dead
students, have filed notices indicating their intent to sue the
school over the fire, and seven plan to sue South Orange or other
governmental entities.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Gov. Christie Whitman signed a law requiring the
installation of automatic sprinkler systems in the state's private
and public school dormitories.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, Seton Hall will have smoke detectors in each room,
plans at least one fire drill per semester, and will have floor
meetings in every dorm to review fire safety plans.
</P>
<P>
   And fire safety is now firmly ingrained in the consciousness of
many Seton Hall students. Merla asked to be assigned to a dorm room
no higher than the second floor; Donato will be on the ground floor
and already has memorized where the fire exits are.
</P>
<P>
   ''I bought a safety ladder,'' Merla said. ''I took a few safety
precautions I wouldn't have thought of last year.''
</P>
<P>
 On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Seton Hall University: http://www.shu.edu
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
