<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood worker accused of sexual assault  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWTON, N.J. (AP) - A worker who had been conducting inspections
of flood-damaged houses in northern New Jersey has been charged
with sexually assaulting a 12-year-old child at one of those homes.
</P>
<P>
   Gliden Rivera, 40, was working for a California-based contractor
hired by the Federal Emergency Management Agency to conduct
inspections of damaged structures for property owners. According to
court papers, the Essex County man later returned to a home in
Hardyston and assaulted the child.
</P>
<P>
   He was charged in Sussex County on Thursday with sexual assault
and child endangerment.
</P>
<P>
   During a Friday court hearing in Newton, state Superior Court
Judge Lorraine Parker noted that Rivera has prior convictions for
similar offenses.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Computer Sciences Corp., Rivera's employer, said
the company did not perform a criminal background check on Rivera
and other employees working under the FEMA contract because they
were not required.
</P>
<P>
   FEMA spokesman Michael Beeman said the contract only required
Computer Sciences to hire people of ''good moral character.'' But
Beeman said that policy will change as of Oct. 1, when the agency
will demand criminal background checks.
</P>
<P>
   It was not known how many homes Rivera had inspected since heavy
rains flooded parts of Sussex and Morris counties on Aug. 12.
President Clinton declared the area a disaster area five days
later, and FEMA officials have been there to help residents apply
for federal aid.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera, who has addresses in Puerto Rico and Newark and who told
the judge that his mother's home in Irvington serves as his
address, was held on $250,000 bail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
