<HEADLINE> Park service seeks input on preserving historic structures  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUSHKILL, Pa. (AP) - Officials at Delaware Water Gap National
Recreation Area are seeking input from area residents on which of
the more than 160 historic properties within the park should be
restored.
</P>
<P>
   In a public meeting Friday in Bushkill, officials presented a
working draft listing each historic property within the 67,000-acre
park and highlighting 33 properties that are vacant and in need of
saving.
</P>
<P>
   A similar meeting is scheduled for Monday in Walpack, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The historic property project, which began two years ago, has
made ''considerable progress,'' said park Superintendent Bill
Laitner.
</P>
<P>
   ''The problem is that there's not too many people willing to
spend what it costs to repair these wonderful pieces of history,''
Laitner said. Some of the properties could cost up to $1 million to
repair, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Park Service must decide which of the properties
are most important to residents in the area before it will continue
with any renovations.
</P>
<P>
   Those attending the meeting didn't favor any one plan over
another, said Zehra Osman, a planner for the National Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   ''They want to preserve buildings. That is what I got from
this,'' Osman said. ''I didn't hear a preference other than save
them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
