<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attorney: Driver asleep, didn't know woman's car went into swamp  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) - The 21-year-old driver charged with
failing to report the accident that caused an 83-year-old
grandmother off a bridge and into a snake-infested swamp didn't
know what he hit because he had fallen asleep, his attorney says.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Andrew Campbell dozed off at the wheel, attorney Lee Cohn
said Friday, which is why he didn't realize he had hit Tillie
Tooter's car. The crash forced Tooter's Toyota off a 40-foot bridge
on Interstate 595 and into a thicket of mangrove and willow trees.
She survived on rainwater for three days before she was discovered.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe he was sleeping,'' Cohn said. ''He told the Florida
Highway Patrol from the get-go that he struck something. He didn't
know if it was debris, a concrete barrier or another car.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell is charged with leaving the scene of an accident scene
with injuries, a felony, and filing a false police report, a
misdemeanor. The FHP arrested Campbell on Thursday, saying he told
troopers shortly after the 3 a.m. Aug. 12 accident he had hit a
retaining wall and did not tell them he had knocked a car off the
bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Tooter had been headed to Fort Lauderdale/Hollywood
International Airport to pick up her granddaughter, Lori Simms of
Marlboro, N.J., whose flight from New Jersey had been delayed, when
she was struck from behind.
</P>
<P>
   The trees cushioned the car's fall and kept it suspended inches
above the swamp's muck and water. Tooter, a Pembroke Pines resident
originally from Brooklyn, was near death from dehydration when she
was discovered by a 15-year-old highway worker. He had noticed an
indentation in the trees and looked over the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Tooter was released from the hospital Aug. 19 and is recovering
at home.
</P>
</TEXT>
