<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Company fined for medical services at prison  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - A company that provides medical services
at a Virginia prison where two Connecticut inmates have died this
year has been fined nearly $1 million over a 13-month period for
failing to live up to its contract, The Hartford Courant reported.
</P>
<P>
   The fines, issued by the Virginia Department of Corrections
against Correctional Medical Services of St. Louis, are for
violations such as poor record-keeping, failing to triage inmates
correctly, failing to assess inmates' conditions and failing to
provide timely referrals, the Courant reported Saturday, citing a
Virginia state auditor's report.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia prison officials said they agreed with the findings and
are working with the company to bring about compliance with the
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 500 Connecticut prisoners were sent to Wallens Ridge
State Prison last year to ease crowding. More than 300 remain at
Wallens Ridge, while 134 have been transferred to the Greenville
Correctional Center in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of medical care is one of several complaints aired by
Wallens Ridge inmates and their advocates, who have also charged
mistreatment of the inmates at the maximum security prison.
</P>
<P>
   The report of fines comes at the same time as another report
that a diabetic inmate who died at Wallens Ridge had claimed in a
lawsuit that prison officials denied him insulin and other medical
care.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Frazier lapsed into a coma after being shocked
repeatedly with a stun gun on June 29. He died July 4.
</P>
<P>
   In a lawsuit filed May 25 in federal court in Roanoke, Frazier
claimed he nearly died on the 22-hour bus trip from Connecticut in
December because he was not given insulin, The Roanoke Times
reported in a copyrighted story for Saturday's editions. After he
arrived in Virginia, Frazier claimed, he was denied insulin on at
least two other occasions.
</P>
<P>
   A judge dismissed Frazier's lawsuit June 23, ruling that
allegations of medical malpractice alone were not enough to support
a claim of cruel and unusual punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia State Auditor Walter J. Kucharski noted that
Correctional Medical Services also failed to provide inmates with a
dentist for three months and has never had an optometrist on duty,
both violations of its contract.
</P>
<P>
   Kucharski told The Courant that there is no evidence to suggest
any prisoner's health has been jeopardized.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Fields, a spokesman for CMS, said his company is working to
improve its service, but added that some of the issues raised by
the audit are beyond the company's control. Inmates cannot be taken
to the infirmary immediately because of security procedures in
high-security prisons such as Wallens Ridge, Fields said.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Michael Lawlor, D-East Haven, said the auditor's
report further convinces him that Connecticut's prisoners should be
returned. Lawlor said state residents should be concerned about the
treatment of Connecticut inmates in Virginia because the $12
million contract between the two states would make Connecticut
liable for potential civil rights lawsuits filed by prisoners or
their families.
</P>
<P>
   Christina Polce, spokeswoman for the Connecticut Department of
Correction, said the department is confident Virginia officials
will address the issues raised in the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
