<HEADLINE> Crenshaw Happy With Earlier Music  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) -- Marshall Crenshaw may be a critics'
darling, but the singer-songwriter insists he has never been
satisfied with his 1982 debut album -- until its recent re-issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was raw and unformed as a singer, kind of groping vocally on
some of those tracks,'' he said. ''I have these criticisms of it,
but I'm fond of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The self-titled album won him raves from critics, but Crenshaw,
whose hits include ''Something's Gonna Happen,'' and ''What Do You
Dream Of?,'' has since struggled for broad commercial success.
</P>
<P>
   While writing songs for his first album, Crenshaw, 46, said he
was ''rediscovering and dealing with'' the rock 'n' roll of his
youth.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was really listening to a lot of rockabilly and getting back
into stuff I knew during childhood and was getting back to it as an
adult,'' he said while promoting a Santa Monica concert scheduled
for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Rhino Records last week simultaneously rereleased his first
album with 10 bonus tracks along with a greatest hits collection
entitled ''This Is Easy: The Best of Marshall Crenshaw''
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw said compiling the music gave him a greater
appreciation for his work.
</P>
<P>
   ''Until I did this 'Best of,' I had this ambivalence about the
records I've made,'' he said. ''But now I just feel like its a good
body of work. Its all kind of resolved for me at this point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
