<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tours given at one of state's oldest prisons and at one of its newest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROMULUS, N.Y. (AP) - It was a chance to see artifacts from one
of the oldest prisons in the state and to tour one of its newest.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday marked open house at the ''big house,'' with tours
offered at Eastern prison in Napanoch and the new $180 million
maximum-security Five Points Correctional Facility in Romulus.
</P>
<P>
   In Ulster County, the Eastern tour was part of an ongoing
centennial celebration of New York's sixth-oldest prison.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors could view Eastern's Braille transcription unit,
historical photos, a video cataloging Eastern's first 100 years and
other artifacts. Some artifacts were even on sale.
</P>
<P>
   Original construction on Eastern began in 1894, and the first
prisoners arrived at the facility on October 1, 1900. In 1921,
Eastern became the Institute for Defective Delinquents. Some 45
years later, due to civil liberties efforts, Eastern resumed its
original function as a reformatory for younger inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1973, it has primarily served as a maximum-security prison
for male felons aged 16 and over. A medium-security, 180-inmate
annex also is on the grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The prison now houses 1,247 inmates and employs approximately
600.
</P>
<P>
   In Romulus, the new prison is being praised by leaders around
Seneca County for its potential boon to the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The prison is built to house 1,500 inmates, scheduled to arrive
this week. With an annual budget of $25 million, it provides 640
full-time jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ''In an ideal world, it would be nice not to have prisons at
all,'' said Glenn Cooke, the county's economic developer. ''But the
fact is, it's not an ideal world. If we are going to have them, we
might as well have them in areas where they fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Sabara, a real estate agent in Ovid, Seneca County, south
of the prison, said the construction brought more renters. And he
estimates housing sales are up about 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The economy was devastated in the 1990s by the downsizing and
eventual closure of the 10,600-acre depot, which had employed more
than 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Residents had opposed a proposal to place the prison on the
former Sampson Air Force Base overlooking Seneca Lake, saying it
would hurt tourism.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Michael F. Nozzolio and others pushed for the current
site, which, at two stories, cannot be seen from nearby highways.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-26-00 1549 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
