<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seattle-based grunge band asks for blanket ban  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) - Pearl Jam is playing it safe this
time.
</P>
<P>
   Two months after nine fans died in a frenzied crush during a set
by the Seattle-based grunge band, its manager asked fans to leave
blankets at home during a concert at Saratoga Performing Arts
Center scheduled for Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We apologize for any inconvenience this may cause, but we have
witnessed a number of injuries as a result of blankets being used
as trampolines at concerts,'' said Pearl Jam manager Kelly Curtis.
''Small beach towels and ponchos will be allowed.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, the company that manages SPAC's outdoor
rock shows forbade blankets. After a public outcry, it relented.
</P>
<P>
   Pearl Jam has affected safety at the amphitheater in the past.
After its 1992 show, metal barriers were installed to prevent stage
rushes.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's soldout show also features Sonic Youth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
