<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Parole backlog in New Jersey bigger than anticipated  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The state attorney general's office has
learned that a backlog of parole cases in New Jersey is much
greater than originally anticipated, news that could complicate
negotiations to settle a lawsuit brought by a group of prison
inmates.
</P>
<P>
   According to a review conducted by the attorney general's
office, 195 additional inmates were found to be eligible for parole
hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks ago, after originally saying the backlog was no more
than several hundred cases, the state attorney general's office
said the number of New Jersey inmates awaiting hearings with the
Parole Board was about 2,800.
</P>
<P>
   But state officials learned that the extent of the problem was
far greater.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, a spokesman for Gov. Christie Whitman said the
backlog had reached a peak of 3,409 cases. Pete McDonough told The
Philadelphia Inquirer for Saturday's editions that a review of
about 4,200 additional files found an additional 195 inmates
eligible for parole hearings with hundreds more reaching
eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   The news came amid the state's negotiations to settle a lawsuit
brought this year by a group of inmates at Riverfront State Prison
in Camden. The lawsuit claims the inmates were incarcerated while
eligible for release.
</P>
<P>
   McDonough said the Whitman administration had hoped to settle
the lawsuit by promising to end the backlog within eight months.
Paul Loriquet, a spokesman for the attorney general's office, said
that timetable is still possible.
</P>
<P>
   Both said the Parole Board has been handling an average of 100
cases per week, but the backlog still stands at 2,700.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Mauer, assistant director of the Sentencing Project in
Washington, D.C., said it is possible that New Jersey has the
largest backlog in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems way out of line, given the evidence we have heard
from other states,'' Mauer said.
</P>
<P>
   Loriquet declined to comment on the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The Parole Board, already facing criticism for its backlog, is
also the subject of a criminal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Consovoy resigned as chairman in July; Robert Egles, the
board's executive director, has taken medical leave; and Peter
Loos, another member, has asked Whitman not to reappoint him.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal investigation involved Consovoy's dealings with
former organized crime figures, including one who was paroled after
a personal hearing with the chairman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
