<HEADLINE> Man gives up job as business consultant to make music for kids  </HEADLINE>
By PAT EATON-ROBB
<TEXT>
<P>
   WETHERSFIELD, Conn. (AP) - Steve Roslonek says he was happy
working for a national consulting firm, solving the business
systems problems of clients across the country.
</P>
<P>
   But he's happier singing to preschoolers about Joey the Frog.
</P>
<P>
   Roslonek, 28, gave up his three-piece suits, professional
salary, and business lunches 1&AMP;frac12; years ago to pursue a risky career
as a children's entertainer and song writer.
</P>
<P>
   He now spends his time writing, recording and performing -
mostly performing. He sets aside two weeks a month for day-care
shows. He's booked through June 2001. The rest of the time he tours
schools and libraries throughout New England.
</P>
<P>
   His new job doesn't pay as well as the old one - he earned about
$70,000 at Anderson Consulting in Hartford, a job he held for over
four years after graduating with an economics degree from Wesleyan
University. Last year, he made about $18,000, before taking into
account the $10,000 he spent on equipment and studio time.
</P>
<P>
   ''But it's not a decision I regret,'' Roslonek said as he
prepared for a recent show before about 200 kids and their parents
at Wethersfield Town Hall. ''Working with kids and writing is
something I feel I was meant to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Roslonek, who grew up in Wethersfield and now lives in Boston,
has become something of a cult figure on New England's kiddie music
circuit. He's not nearly as well known as artists like Raffi, but
many who have heard his music become devoted fans.
</P>
<P>
   Marguerite Alpert, of Wethersfield, said her 3-year-old daughter
Grace saw her first ''Steve concert'' in December. After the show,
Grace began carrying his picture with her everywhere, calling him
''my Steve.'' Her family has been to see Roslonek six times since
then, and paid for him to play a concert in their neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   His high-energy delivery gets his little listeners involved
acting out the lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   ''He makes a connection, because he can be really goofy, and
he's genuinely warm,'' she said. ''He obviously has a clear memory
of his boyhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of his songs also appeal to parents, including this song
about a boy who wants his ice cream, but doesn't want to eat his
peas to get it:
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a pea on my plate
</P>
<P>
   that my mother put there.
</P>
<P>
   Peas make me vomit,
</P>
<P>
   but she doesn't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Roslonek wrote his first children's song for the daughter of a
girlfriend in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was just so fun, and people liked it,'' he said. ''I just
couldn't stop. They just kind of wrote themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   His first album, ''Morning 'Til Night,'' was released in
December 1998. He quit his consulting job two months later.
</P>
<P>
   Some of coworkers thought he was crazy, said Sandy Fenton, of
East Hampton. She worked with Roslonek at Anderson, and now brings
her three children to see him sing.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once I heard his music, I knew right away that he was going to
succeed,'' she said. ''He was very good at what he did and the
management thought very highly of him. They were very sad when he
left, but I think they knew he had to follow his heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Roslonek doesn't have a big recording contract. He markets his
music over the Internet and sells his CDs at shows. In May his
first CD won an award from the Parents' Choice Foundation. His
second CD, ''On a Flying Guitar,'' came out in July.
</P>
<P>
   He has developed different shows for different age levels,
offering songs about spinning and playing for toddlers. But at
elementary schools, he will put on workshops for third-, fourth-
and fifth-graders, helping them write songs about whatever they are
studying.
</P>
<P>
   ''All the stuff I like about consulting, I still get to do every
day,'' he said. ''I really liked creating things, creative problem
solving, and working with people.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve hopes to make it big someday, and play before thousands of
fans in concert halls. But for now, he's happy with a career that
lets him lead a conga line of giggling, singing 4-year-olds through
the town halls, libraries and day-care centers across New England.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like going downstairs for Christmas and not knowing what
you're going to get, but knowing you're going to be excited about
it, '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Steve Roslonek: http://www.stevesongs.com
</P>
<P>
   Steve Roslonek downloads:
http://artists.mp3s.com/artists/46/stevesongs--steve-roslone.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
