<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Affiliate: Congo Abuses Abound  </HEADLINE>
By ARNAUD ZAJTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) -- A U.N. human rights investigator has
accused Congo's government and rebels of continued abuses in the
war-divided Central African nation, citing the jailing of political
opponents and reports of civilian massacres.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Garreton, a Chilean lawyer who in the past has accused
both sides of killings and torture, was making his third visit to
Congo in the past two years. During a news briefing Friday at the
end of his 13-day trip, he said killings are the biggest problem in
rebel-held areas of the country, while improper jailings are common
in government-controlled regions.
</P>
<P>
   Garreton's trip included stops in several regions to examine
human rights issues and the condition of detention facilities. He
said there had been some improvements in government-held areas, but
he noted that he was denied access to some facilities there. He
also said the government has jailed political opponents and
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   In rebel-controlled areas, civilians are living in fear in the
wake of recent massacres, Garreton said. He said civilians
allegedly had been killed because they helped traditional Mayi-Mayi
fighters, who are backing the government of President Laurent
Kabila. He did not offer details.
</P>
<P>
   Garreton said no independent newspapers or radio stations were
allowed to operate in rebel-held areas.
</P>
<P>
   He applauded both the government and a Rwandan-backed rebel
faction for beginning to demobilize child soldiers, while singling
out Uganda for continuing to use them in parts of Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Garreton plans to release a full report in November, but he
noted that his reports generally ''have little effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the United Nations and Congo have been
strained ever since U.N. officials began investigating massacres of
Rwandan Hutu refugees -- allegedly by forces loyal to Kabila and
aided by Rwanda and Uganda. The United Nations sent human rights
experts to Congo in June 1997 to investigate the massacres, but
withdrew them 10 months later because of what it called a total
lack of cooperation from the Congolese government.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting in Congo restarted in 1998 when rebel forces backed by
Rwanda and Uganda tried to oust Kabila, who had support from
Angola, Namibia and Zimbabwe. The Rwanda-Uganda alliance fell apart
after they backed rival rebel groups, and the two countries turned
their guns on each other in June in the city of Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
   Under a peace agreement signed last summer, 5,537 U.N. observers
were to be stationed in Congo to supervise a cease-fire and the
withdrawal of foreign forces. So far, only 264 U.N. military
observers and about 15 international staff have been deployed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
