<HEADLINE> Town hall spat turns physical  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. (AP) - A town known of late for its scandals
can now add town hall shoving matches to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Police say Town Supervisor Ann Barcher and Councilwoman Marlene
Galow engaged in a physical confrontation at town hall Friday,
apparently over an ongoing investigation into the assessor's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Barcher said Galow entered her office uninvited, and accused
Barcher of stealing the computer. Barcher had just given police the
computer hard drive as evidence in the probe.
</P>
<P>
   Barcher said Galow wouldn't leave, and began flailing her arms
when Barcher opened a door to the hallway. Barcher said she then
tried to shove Galow out of the office.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had to physically eject her from my office because she
refused to leave,'' Barcher said, calm and looking unmarked from
the scuffle. ''I will clean up the town. ''If that means an
investigation of the assessor's office, well...''
</P>
<P>
   Barcher said she was planning to file a formal complaint with
police against Galow following the incident. Police photographed
what Barcher said was a mark on her neck where Galow apparently hit
her, according to Barcher.
</P>
<P>
   Galow would not comment on any police action that may have been
taken. However, she did say she hired two lawyers to look into the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   Barcher, a Democrat, and the Democrat-dominated town board have
been at odds since first coming into office in January. Before last
November's election, Galow and Barcher were frequent political
allies. But Democrat Galow and other town board members often
disagree with the supervisor on issues - most recently the board's
intention to hire a town administrator who would replace the
supervisor as Poughkeepsie's day-to-day manager.
</P>
<P>
   The town has been under a federal probe since assessor Basil
Raucci disappeared on Oct. 4 1997, the day after being confronted
by an FBI agent. His body was found in the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, two town officials were convicted on corruption-related
charges. Other things that have happened here include: a mother of
two being shot to death leaving church choir practice; a political
boss's conviction of running a shakedown scheme; the town water
supervisor's firing a bullet into his head as police came to his
door; the aforesaid official being accused of orchestrating a
lesbian tryst in a town pump station.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
