<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ivory Coast Vote Postpone Requested  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) -- The National Electoral Commission
has asked Ivory Coast's junta to postpone next month's presidential
elections so it can better prepare for the vote that is to return
the country to civilian rule, officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Commission President Honore Guie said the body needs more time
to register voters, prepare election guidelines and order and
distribute balloting materials before the Sept. 17 vote.
</P>
<P>
   The commission requested that the first round of voting be
postponed until Oct. 15 or Oct. 22, he said in a statement
broadcast on state-run radio and television. A second round will be
organized if no candidate wins more than 50 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate response from the ruling military junta.
</P>
<P>
   The elections come amid mounting tension in Ivory Coast, which
was considered a bastion of stability in volatile West Africa
before a Dec. 24 coup.
</P>
<P>
   Although the military takeover was initially popular among
Ivorians, who had grown tired of corruption and ethnic favoritism
under ousted President Henri Konan Bedie, many have since become
disillusioned with the new regime.
</P>
<P>
   Disgruntled soldiers have mutinied twice over bonuses and perks
they say they were promised for supporting the coup. There has been
no improvement in the economy, which has been hobbled by plummeting
prices for the country's main exports, cocoa and coffee. And many
believe the junta's policies are fueling the same ethnic tensions
that divided the country under Bedie.
</P>
<P>
   Junta leader Gen. Robert Guei is among 19 candidates who have
registered with the electoral commission to run for president. The
candidacies must be approved by the Supreme Court, which has until
Sept. 2 to confirm their eligibility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
