<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plattsburgh mill may be sold  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PLATTSBURGH, N.Y. (AP) - Negotiations are underway for Georgia
Pacific's mill here to be sold, company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The plan is to continue to run the mill as it is run,'' said
spokeswoman Marta Pauer-Tursi. She acknowledged, however, that once
the plant is sold, it will have no control over that.
</P>
<P>
   With 527 workers, Georgia-Pacific is Plattsburgh's
second-largest employer, with an annual payroll of about $25
million.
</P>
<P>
   As Pauer-Tursi spoke with reporters Friday, employees at the
plant were being informed about the potential sale.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an honor really,'' said Peter Seguin, president of Paper
Allied Chemical and Energy Local 140, which represents about 90
paper makers. ''If it wasn't a profitable mill and it wasn't
technologically advanced, it wouldn't be considered.''
</P>
<P>
   Some employees were less enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of people are very uncomfortable,'' said Timothy
Barnard, president of PACE Local 387, representing about 350
maintenance, yard and converting employees.
</P>
<P>
   Local 387 Vice President Randolph Holloway said he doesn't know
what the result will be. ''We don't even know who they (the buyers)
are,'' he said. ''If they're going to tell us we're on the trading
block, they ought to tell us who it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific's mill here will likely be sold in a divestiture
aimed at smoothing the way for an $11 billion acquisition of Fort
James Corp.
</P>
<P>
   A potential buyer has expressed an interest, and negotiations
are under way, according to the local plant's communications
manager, Marta Pauer-Tursi.
</P>
<P>
   The sale is to be a package deal, she added. The buyer would
also purchase Georgia-Pacific's mills in Greenwich; Brattleboro,
Vt.; Gary, Ind.; Flagstaff, Ariz.; suburban Chicago; and LaGrange,
Ga.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
