<HEADLINE> Explosives Found in England Woods  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- A cache of sophisticated explosives has been found
in a rural wooded area in southern England, police said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The devices were discovered by a man walking his dog in the
woods in Oxfordshire on Friday afternoon, police said. ''These
devices are, in the opinion of our experts, extremely sophisticated
and extremely dangerous,'' said Detective Superintendent John
Donlon.
</P>
<P>
   Police found eight handmade explosive devices buried at the site
70 miles west of London. The clear plastic water bottles were
filled with seven pounds of brass nuts and were designed to explode
if disturbed or handled, Donlon said.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-terrorist officers and an army bomb-disposal squad were
called to the scene, and some of the devices were taken away for
forensic examination.
</P>
<P>
   The explosives were similar to one found on a wall in
Cheltenham, western England, on Aug. 20, Donlon said. He said no
group had claimed responsibility for the devices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
