<DOCNO> APW20000826.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan General: No Early Election  </HEADLINE>
By AMIR ZIA
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Military ruler Gen. Pervez Musharraf
won't bow to demands for an early return to democracy, but will
abide by the Supreme Court's three-year deadline for elections,
Pakistan's Foreign Ministry said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf met with Commonwealth Secretary-General Don McKinnon,
who said Friday on his arrival in Islamabad that his group would
like to see elections in Pakistan ''earlier rather than later.''
The Commonwealth is an organization of Britain and its former
colonies.
</P>
<P>
   During his meeting with McKinnon, Musharraf reviewed his
government's plans to revive Pakistan's ailing economy and
implement political reforms, a Foreign Ministry statement said.
Musharraf promised to complete the reforms within the Supreme
Court-imposed deadline of three years, but no sooner, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Saturday, McKinnon met Pakistani President Rafiq Tarrar and
Foreign Minister Abdul Sattar. During meetings with Pakistan's
leaders, McKinnon discussed the problem of corruption in emerging
democracies, the Foreign Ministry statement said without
elaborating.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, McKinnon will meet with leaders of political parties
and representatives of human rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   The Commonwealth suspended Pakistan's membership soon after the
military coup that ousted the country's elected government last
October. Since then, it has pressed the military-led government to
relinquish power and pave the way for the country's return to
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   But there is little domestic pressure on Musharraf for elections
in a country which has been ruled by the army for 25 years of its
53-year history. Musharraf accuses deposed premier Nawaz Sharif's
government of relentless corruption, destroying institutions,
undermining the constitution and responsibility for the country's
economic turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   He has formed the National Accountability Bureau and set up
special courts with sweeping powers to arrest, investigate and try
politicians, bureaucrats and businessmen accused of graft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-26-00 1754 </TRAILER>
