<HEADLINE> Residents Kidnap Mexican Officials  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALTAMIRANO, Mexico (AP) -- Hundreds of residents of a largely
Indian village in southern Mexico kidnapped two officials, their
secretaries and eight others on Friday to demand $100,000 to build
a much-needed road.
</P>
<P>
   The kidnapping at the local district attorney's office came
shortly after a road commission rejected a request for a rural road
in Chiapas state. Assistant District Attorney Mariano Lopez Perez
was trying to negotiate the captives' release late Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Such actions are common in impoverished Chiapas, where Zapatista
rebels led an uprising in 1994 to demand greater Indian rights. A
partial accord was signed in 1996, but peace talks later broke
down. The Zapatistas have refused to resume negotiations, claiming
the government has failed to abide by the 1996 agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
