<HEADLINE> Express Tour Wins Stallion Stakes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Express Tour breezed to victory in the Affirmed
Division of the $125,000 Florida Stallion Stakes at Calder Race
Course on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Silk Concorde was the runaway winner of the Susan's Girl
Division for fillies. Both events were the second legs of the
three-race series for 2-year olds.
</P>
<P>
   Florida-bred Express Tour, ridden by Julio Garcia, won the
Affirmed by 11&AMP;frac14; lengths over Radical Riley, a 70-1 shot, with Sir
Brian's Sword third in the seven-furlong race.
</P>
<P>
   Express Tour was timed in 1:23 4-5 and Silk Concorde in 1:23
2-5, in each case a stakes record. Express Tour paid $6.40, $4.40,
and $2.60; Radical Riley $36 and $10.60; and Sir Brian's Sword
$3.60.
</P>
<P>
   In the Susan's Girl, Silk Concorde, with Javier Castellon
aboard, finished ahead of stablemate Valid Forbes by 5&AMP;frac34; lengths.
Dream Me was third in the seven-furlong race.
</P>
<P>
   Silk Concorde paid $3.80, $2.10, and $2.10.; Valid Forbes $2.10
and $2.10; and Dream Me also paid $2.10.
</P>
<P>
   Express Tour is in position to earn $290,000 if he can win the
final phase of the Stallion Stakes series-- the In-Reality Division
at a 1 1-16 miles on Oct. 7. Having won the six- and seven-furlong
phases of the series, Express Tour is eligible for a $50,000 bonus
in addition to the $240,000 winner's purse in the Dr. Fager finale.
</P>
<P>
   Express Tour was crowded at the start and was fifth as Condensed
Version went to the front. Express Tour moved up quickly and took
the lead on the rail leaving the seven-furlong chute.
</P>
<P>
   Condensed Version stayed within a length of Express Tour to the
stretch turn. From that point, it was a one-horse race. Radical
Riley rallied on the outside for second, 1&AMP;frac14; lengths ahead of Sir
Brian's Sword.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the My Dear Girl division for fillies will win
just $240,000 because Silk Concorde finished second to Valid Forbes
in the six-furlong filly series opener.
</P>
<P>
   Silk Concorde, the daughter of Concorde's Tune, was second to
Who's Tune, three lengths off the pace, at the five-eighths pole.
She cut the deficit to a half-length going into the far turn.
</P>
<P>
   At the quarter pole, Silk Concorde had a length lead over Dream
Me before she opened a huge lead in midstretch and was not
threatened by Vaild Forbes' late run.
</P>
</TEXT>
