<DOCNO> APW20000826.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yankees 10, Athletics 6  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Clay Bellinger tripled twice and drove in
three runs to help Orlando Hernandez win his second straight start
as the New York Yankees defeated the Oakland Athletics 10-6 on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez (10-10), who had lost four straight decisions before
winning his last two, struck out a season-high 11 in seven innings.
He gave up three runs, five hits and three walks.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Mulder (7-10) allowed six runs and 10 hits in two-plus
innings, his shortest outing of the year. He walked one and struck
out one as he lost for the eighth time in 10 decisions since June
30.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams, who missed the previous seven games with a
strained right rib cage, singled in the first inning to score Derek
Jeter. Tino Martinez added a two-run single in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Sojo had an RBI single in the second and Jose Canseco hit
his 12th homer leading off the third. It was the 443rd homer of his
career, which moves him into sole possession of 23rd place on the
career list.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Posada doubled homer Martinez to make it 6-0 and end
Mulder's day.
</P>
<P>
   Bellinger tripled home two runs and Jeter added a sacrifice fly
in the fifth against reliever Omar Olivares.
</P>
<P>
   Bellinger was also credited with a triple when Terrence Long
lost his fly ball in the sun in the seventh, scoring Scott Brosius.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Chavez hit his 19th homer, a two-run shot off Hernandez in
the third, and Frank Menechino hit a three-run homer in the ninth
off Mike Stanton.
</P>
<P>
   Mariano Rivera got one out for his 28th save in 33 chances.
</P>
<P>
Notes: The Yankees are 33-19 since July 1, the best record in the
AL. ... Williams snapped an 0-for-12 streak with his first-inning
single. ... The A's lead the majors with 117 errors. ... Mulder is
the first A's rookie to lose 10 games in a season since Chris
Codiroli went 12-12 and Tim Conroy was 7-10 in 1983. ... A's LHP
Mike Magnante has allowed one run in his last 15 appearances (10
2-3 innings) ... Long, who had his first career four hit game,
leads all rookies in runs scored (80). ... Canseco, who spent parts
of nine seasons with the A's, has hit 122 homers in the Oakland
Coliseum, his most at any ballpark.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-26-00 1940 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000826.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blazers, Cavs, Heat To Seal Deal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- There have been no snags with Portland's
trade plans, and Shawn Kemp should be a member of the Trail Blazers
and Brian Grant a member of the Miami Heat by the end of next week.
</P>
<P>
   The parties agreed to the deal two weeks ago, and it could
officially happen as early as Wednesday, The Oregonian reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers will acquire Kemp, a six-time All-Star, from
Cleveland. They will send Grant to Miami and Gary Grant to the
Cavaliers. The Heat will trade Chris Gatling and Clarence
Weatherspoon, along with a first-round draft pick and cash, to the
Cavaliers.
</P>
<P>
   Miami also wants to send guard Harold Jamison to the Blazers, a
move that would enable Brian Grant's new seven-year contract to
jump from about $84 million to $89 million.
</P>
<P>
   The possible addition of Jamison, who would see little laying
time with the Blazers, is not expected to be a deal breaker, The
Oregonian reported.
</P>
<P>
   The trade was delayed because of an NBA rule that prevented
Miami from dealing Gatling until Aug. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, the holdup will allow Blazers president and
general manager Bob Whitsitt to return from a family vacation in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ''You never say never, but no, I don't see anything at this
stage that could stop this trade from happening,'' said Kemp's
agent, Tony Dutt. ''I'm not aware of any issues or anything that
could change the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Kemp, 30, has worn out his welcome after three seasons in
Cleveland with a bad attitude and with his struggles to stay in
shape. But he still has plenty of offensive skills.
</P>
<P>
   ''Shawn is really excited about coming to Portland,'' Dutt said.
''We think mentally this is where he needs to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant opted out of the remaining four years and $40 million on
his previous contract, primarily because he knew the Blazers were
interested in acquiring Kemp. Like Kemp, Grant is looking forward
to a change of scenery.
</P>
<P>
   ''Miami is Miami. It's a paradise,'' Grant said. ''You've got
beaches and all those types of things. It's not Portland -- I can't
go salmon fishing -- and there is no city like Portland. But I don't
want to start comparing cities.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant could re-sign with the Blazers and refuse a trade. But
under league rules, Portland still could trade him after Dec. 15 --
to Cleveland or any other team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-26-00 1946 </TRAILER>
