<DOCNO> APW20000826.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four Die in Russia Market Stampede  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAKHACHKALA, Russia (AP) -- A rumor that a bomb had been found
set off a stampede in a crowded market Saturday, killing four
people and injuring 17, officials in the Russian republic of
Dagestan said.
</P>
<P>
   The victims died when they rushed to squeeze through the
market's narrow exits in Khasavyurt, a town near the border with
the breakaway republic of Chechnya, Dagestan's Interior Ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
   There were about 5,000 people in the market when the rumor
spread. No bomb was found in a subsequent search, said a ministry
spokesman in Makhachkala, Dagestan's capital.
</P>
<P>
   Khasavyurt is in a part of Dagestan that was invaded twice last
year by Chechnya-based rebels seeking to carve out an Islamic
state. A car bomb earlier this month killed two people in the town.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-26-00 2016 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000826.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressL. Bryce Boyer:
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Dr. L. Bryce Boyer, a psychoanalyst who
advanced the idea that analysts may experience emotional reactions
to patients that reflect their own inner conflicts and needs, died
Aug. 9. He was 84.
</P>
<P>
   Boyer held the unpopular view that countertransference could be
an important tool in helping patients.
</P>
<P>
   Boyer lectured throughout the United States and Europe and found
that his peers abroad, especially in South America, held a more
favorable view of the idea.
</P>
<P>
   He also argued in favor of using psychoanalysis not only for the
''worried well,'' he said, but also for people with serious
psychological illnesses such as addiction, borderline pathology and
psychosis.
</P>
<P>
   Boyer founded the Boyer House, a nonprofit residential
psychoanalytic treatment center, in San Rafael.
Ed Grennan:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Ed Grennan, a longtime Chicago television and
radio host, died Tuesday of a heart attack. He was 78.
</P>
<P>
   Grennan, whose career in Chicago broadcasting spanned 50 years,
most recently appeared as a supporting actor in the critically
acclaimed movie, ''The Straight Story.''
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1950s, he was one of the first disc jockeys at
WLS-AM, playing Dixie, jazz and rock music. He also worked at
WGN-AM and WAIT-AM before moving to NBC, where he spent nearly 30
years until he retired in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   At NBC's WMAQ-FM, he was the host of ''Problems and Solutions.''
It was on that show that he took calls from listeners and offered
advice.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1960s he was the host of television games shows such
as ''Everything's Relative.''
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife, three daughters, three sons and two
grandchildren.
Leonard Japp:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Leonard Japp Sr., widely recognized as the
entrepreneur behind the modern, corn oil-fried potato chip, died
Thursday. He was 96.
</P>
<P>
   Japp founded Jays Foods, whose slogan is ''Can't stop eating
'em.''
</P>
<P>
   He saw his company grow from a two-person operation delivering
nuts and pretzels to Al Capone's speakeasies in 1927 to a business
that currently employs 1,000 people and sells snacks in Illinois,
Indiana, Wisconsin, Michigan, Missouri, Minnesota and Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   The name of the company's leading house brand, Mrs. Japp's
chips, fell victim to anti-Japanese sentiment after the bombing of
Pearl Harbor in 1941 and disappeared from grocery store shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Japp quickly changed the company's name, then known as Special
Foods Co., to Jays Foods.
</P>
<P>
   Jays grew to $64 million in annual sales by 1986 and the family
sold the company to Borden Inc. But by 1994, Jays was losing $17
million a year, prompting the family and other investors to buy it
back.
Serge Lebovici:
</P>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- Serge Lebovici, a noted child psychiatrist and the
only Frenchman to head the International Psychoanalytic
Association, died of heart failure Aug. 12. He was 85.
</P>
<P>
   Born June 10, 1915, Lebovici was the son of a Jewish doctor who
was deported to Auschwitz by the Nazis during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   He was professor of child psychiatry at the University of
Paris-North and founded numerous professional associations
dedicated to the study of mental illness among children.
</P>
<P>
   Lebovici was also the author or co-author of numerous works,
including ''Understanding the Child through Psychoanalysis,'' ''The
Infant, the Mother and the Psychoanalyst,'' and ''New Treatments
for the Child and Adolescent.''
Lynden Pindling:
</P>
<P>
   NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) -- Former Prime Minister Lynden Pindling,
leader of the Bahamas for 25 years, died Saturday of prostate
cancer. He was 70.
</P>
<P>
   Pindling became premier in 1967 when the islands were still a
British colony, and led the Bahamas to independence in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   However, his reputation suffered from never-proven allegations
of bribery and protecting drug traffickers, which clouded the
country's relations with the United States and contributed to
Pindling's defeat in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Pindling's policies helped create a large black middle class by
broadening educational opportunities for the country's 172,000
people. But the Bahamas also became a major drug-trafficking haven
under his tenure in the late 1970s and 1980s, which critics blamed
on government inaction.
</P>
<P>
   A series of scandals -- he was accused of covering up for drug
lords in the 1980s and taking bribes as chairman of the state Hotel
Commission -- contributed to his party's downfall. It won only six
of the 40 seats in the National Assembly in the March 1997
elections, when Ingraham gained a second term.
</P>
<P>
   A government commission was unable to substantiate any of the
claims against Pindling.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his conflicted past, Bahamians mourned the loss of the
leader known as the ''Black Moses,'' who helped found the
Progressive Liberal Party in 1953 as a grass-roots opposition to
the mostly white colonial-run United Bahamian Party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
