<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Gen.: Radical Islam a Danger  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- The newly appointed chief of Turkey's
powerful army warned that any concessions to radical Islam would
pull the country back to the Middle Ages, newspapers reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey's military leaders have spearheaded the secular state's
battle against Islamic political movements, identifying them as one
of the main threats to the republic.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Hilmi Ozkok, speaking Friday at his inauguration as army
chief, said radical Islamic factions ''aim to destroy the successes
of Turkey's democratic and secular republic, which is based on the
rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is clear that any deviation or concession on these basic
principles will bring this country to the darkness of the Middle
Ages,'' Ozkok was quoted as saying by the Sabah daily.
</P>
<P>
   Ozkok's statements come amid a controversy that pits President
Ahmet Necdet Sezer against Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit.
</P>
<P>
   Ecevit has accused the president of encouraging radical Islam by
refusing to sign a decree that would let the government sack
thousands of civil servants suspected of sympathizing with Islamic
factions. Sezer said the decree was unconstitutional because it
lacked parliament's approval.
</P>
<P>
   The government will present the decree to parliament when it
convenes in October, and the military has already urged lawmakers
to swiftly adopt the bill. But the decree is likely to face strong
opposition in parliament, which is dominated by conservative and
Islamic lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The military has carried out three coups since 1960. It
pressured Turkey's first Islamic-led government out of office in
1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
