<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Packers 34, Browns 33  </HEADLINE>
By GREG BEACHAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- The Green Bay Packers' defensive starters
finally stopped somebody -- even if it was only the Cleveland
Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay's first-string defense forced its first two punts of
the preseason and Bill Schroeder caught two touchdown passes as the
Packers held on to beat the Browns 34-33 Saturday night in the
NFL's final preseason game.
</P>
<P>
   Backup fullback Matt Snider caught a short pass from Danny
Wuerffel and rumbled 66 yards for the go-ahead touchdown with 5:28
left.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns made a late scoring drive on five straight passes
from Kevin Thompson to Dennis Northcutt -- including a 26-yard TD
pass with 50 seconds left -- but Thompson's pass to Northcutt on the
two-point conversion attempt was low and wide.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Hasselbeck and Wuerffel each threw two touchdown passes in
place of Brett Favre, who watched in shorts and a T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Favre, who rested the tendinitis in his right elbow for the
third straight game, hasn't played since the first two series in
Green Bay's preseason opener on Aug. 4. But he is expected to play
next week against the New York Jets, keeping alive his NFL-record
streak of 125 consecutive starts.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers' defense, still learning the scheme of new
coordinator Ed Donatell, forced Cleveland to punt on its first two
possessions. Of course, the Browns had just six points in their
last eight quarters of play prior to the game.
</P>
<P>
   Embattled quarterback Tim Couch again struggled to spark the
Browns' offense, but Cleveland scored its first touchdown since the
preseason opener when Errict Rhett dove in from 1 yard with 11:09
left in the second quarter. Couch, who didn't practice until
Thursday while resting a sore arm, was 7-of-11 for 96 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland (1-3) lost its final three preseason games, while
Green Bay (2-2) won both of its home exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   Hasselbeck had another outstanding game, completing 10 of 12
passes for 137 yards and two touchdowns while leading the Packers
on three scoring drives. He hit Schroeder for TD passes of 24 and
16 yards in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams played their starters into the second quarter, and
the real competition for jobs began in the second half. Among the
young Browns making the best impressions were Rashidi Barnes and
fellow rookie defensive back Anthony Malbrough, who played tight
defense in place of injured starter Daylon McCutcheon.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Travis Prentice solidified his backup spot behind Rhett
by rushing for 55 yards and a touchdown, while rookie quarterback
Spergon Wynn led two scoring drives in the fourth quarter and
Thompson another. Still, the Browns are expected to sign or trade
for a veteran backup quarterback sometime this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes returned an interception 83 yards for a touchdown with
1:09 left in the second quarter. Barnes darted in front of a Green
Bay receiver to pick off Wuerffel's quick slant pass, then dodged
Wuerffel downfield and outran the Packers to score.
</P>
<P>
   In a mild surprise, Herbert ''Whisper'' Goodman appeared to
decisively win his battle with Basil Mitchell for the Packers' last
running back spot.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman, a rookie from NAIA Division II Graceland (Iowa), rushed
for 88 yards on 21 carries and also caught three passes for a
team-high 67 yards, while Mitchell -- playing mostly with the
Packers' starters -- was stymied with just 15 yards on 11 carries.
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Kevin Johnson returned for Cleveland after missing two
games with a hamstring pull, but he strained the hamstring again
and was taken out. Starting cornerback Corey Fuller sprained a toe
and also left early.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay plays host to the Jets next Sunday, while the Browns
play Jacksonville.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-26-00 2025 </TRAILER>
