<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Triathlete Closes in on Goal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) -- Marathon swimmer Jim Dreyer conquered
his fourth Great Lake, but he wasn't finished with his
ultra-triathlon.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyer touched the shore of Toronto around 7 p.m. Saturday after
running a marathon of 26.2 miles, biking 112 miles and swimming
Lake Ontario over two days, according to his Web site, which
periodically posted updates on his progress.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyer started swimming south after the touchdown, with a goal
of reaching Niagara-on-the-Lake, N.Y., by Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   During his swim across Lake Ontario, which began Friday night,
his goggles leaked causing the water to swell his right eye,
according to the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The Byron Center native failed to complete his first endurance
test last month due to dehydration and fatigue. This time around,
he planned a nonstop athletic feat that would cover 201.4 total
miles if completed.
</P>
<P>
   He was near the end of his feat and needed only to turn right
back around and swim back to Niagara-On-The-Lake for a total of
63.2 swimming miles.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Dreyer has spent nearly 36 hours of continuous running,
biking, and swimming. There's an estimated 18-26 hours of swimming
left.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyer, 37, started his marathon-length run Friday morning. He
originally planned to begin around 7 a.m., though the exact time he
actually started was unclear. His Web site did not note his
starting time.
</P>
<P>
   The site said Dreyer completed the run shortly after 1 p.m. Ten
minutes later, after changing gear, he started the bicycling
portion of the event.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyer earlier said he figured to spend about 12 hours running
and biking and another 46 hours swimming, meaning his attempt would
end sometime Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
   All of Dreyer's athletic tests have been to raise money for Big
Brothers Big Sisters of America, a youth-mentoring program.
</P>
<P>
   On July 24, Dreyer set out to swim Lake Erie, run 26.2 miles,
bike 112 miles and then swim Lake Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyer swam 26 miles across Lake Erie and completed the run, but
stopped before bicycling because he suffered dehydration and
cramping and could not remain conscious. His body temperature
dropped to 93.7 degrees, and he had to wrap himself in blankets to
ease shivering.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyer, who swam across Lake Michigan in 1998 and Lake Huron in
1999, told The Grand Rapids Press before starting his most recent
feat that he expected a tough mental challenge after reaching
Toronto, the halfway point of his swim.
</P>
<P>
   ''The toughest part of this thing is going to Toronto and not
getting out of the water,'' he said. ''Getting out in Toronto is
not an option. You can't even have that thought in the back of your
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   In training for this ultra-triathlon, Dreyer said he has worked
with a sports nutritionist in the hope of avoiding the severe
cramping that doomed his last effort.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Jim Dreyer's Web site: http://www.swimjimswim.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-26-00 2034 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
