<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albany Times-Union editor dies at 40  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CLIFTON PARK, N.Y. (AP) - Karen Potter, managing editor for
features at the Albany Times Union, died in her home Saturday after
battling a rare form of bone cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma-reared and Texas-trained, Potter combined a small-town
humility with a fearlessness in taking on powerful interests and
outsized personalities that she developed during a decade covering
Lone Star State politics for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
</P>
<P>
   Former Texas Gov. Ann Richards remembered Potter as ''a
tenacious reporter'' who buttonholed the Democratic governor daily,
''even sometimes when I wished fervently not to see another
newspaper reporter.'' But Potter, he said, stood out from the
statehouse press corps in Austin as ''a little more gracious in her
manner, a little more thoughtful in her questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Co-workers at the Times Union remembered Potter for displaying
the soul of a social worker. ''I want to make a difference,''
Potter said in an application letter to the Times Union. She joined
the paper in 1995 and fulfilled that promise, said Jeff Cohen,
Times Union vice president and editor.
</P>
<P>
   ''Karen embodied what is right about journalism,'' Cohen said.
''Her priorities were fine writing, unshakable ethics and editing
features sections that challenged our readers.''
</P>
<P>
   In lieu of flowers, contributions should be made to Ewing's
Sarcoma Research, University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center,
Box 910888, Dallas, TX 75391-0888.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-26-00 2039 </TRAILER>
