<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yemen Opposition Leaders Arrested  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN'A, Yemen (AP) -- Police arrested five leaders of Yemen's
largest opposition group Saturday, accusing them of meeting without
a permit, police and party officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Police detained the Socialist party leaders as they met in the
southern city of Aden to prepare for a national convention due to
be held in the capital, San'a, on Aug. 30.
</P>
<P>
   ''The police excuses are weak,'' said Mohamed Abdel Wahid, the
Socialist party's chief of information. ''The Yemeni Socialist
party is a legitimate party operating with an official government
license and, therefore, is free to operate in public without the
need of an official police permit.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those detained was Ali Monasser Mohammed, the secretary
general of the party's San'a bureau, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The party has often accused the government of undemocratic
practices. It boycotted last year's presidential elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
