<HEADLINE> Diner was setting of Paul Newman's ''Nobody's Fool''  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BEACON, N.Y. (AP) - A 1930's diner that was the setting for
scenes in the Paul Newman film ''Nobody's Fool'' was badly damaged
by fire early Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fire started after no one was here,'' waitress Mindy
Bentley said. ''I didn't even know this happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Beacon City Fire Chief Dennis Fahey said the cause of the fire
was accidental. One firefighter suffered burns to his hands and was
treated at the scene, he said. There were no other injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The diner was known as Tiffany's Diner in 1994, when the movie
was shot.
</P>
<P>
   Beacon is 50 miles north of Manhattan.	   
</P>
