<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Skimming Wins Pacific Classsic  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL MAR, Calif. (AP) -- Skimming led the entire way for a
two-length victory in the $1 million Pacific Classic on Saturday,
giving trainer Bobby Frankel his fifth win in the 10-year history
of the race.
</P>
<P>
   General Challenge, the defending champion and a 9-10 favorite,
placed fourth with substitute jockey Laffit Pincay Jr. riding. He
drew the mount after Corey Nakatani was injured two races earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Skimming, with Garrett Gomez aboard, paid $11.40, $6.40 and
$4.80 in the race over 1&AMP;frac14; miles for 3-year-olds and up at Del Mar.
</P>
<P>
   Nakatani broke his left collarbone in a fall while riding
Candance in Paris in the sixth race. The tumble came on the final
turn when Candance in Paris clipped heals with Elderberry, which
was called for interference and given last place after finishing
second.
</P>
<P>
   The injury is expected to sideline Nakatani up to five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Candance in Paris, which broke a shoulder, was humanely
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Tiznow, the only 3-year-old in the seven-horse field, finished
1&AMP;frac14; lengths ahead of Ecton Park. General Challenge came from the
back of the field to finish a half-length behind Ecton Park.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel recorded four straight victories in the race from
1992-95, including the last two with Tinners Way.
</P>
<P>
   ''This (latest win) ranks up there,'' Frankel said. ''They are
all great. The first has to be the best. But this is a horse that
was sent to me without high expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Skimming, owned by Juddmonte Farms, came off an eight-length
victory in the San Diego Handicap at Del Mar on Aug. 6. Since
starting with Frankel in March, Skimming has four wins, a second
and a third in six races.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were cooking out there. I knew that,'' Gomez said. ''I was
just riding him the way Bobby told me to. Bobby said, 'Leave him
alone and let him do what he wants.' So I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Gomez, 28, won on his first mount in the Pacific Classic. He
rode at Del Mar in 1994 and became a Southern California regular in
late 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay, who picked up two mounts during the day, had his seventh
ride of the day on General Challenge and finished with eight mounts
on the 10-race card.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the half-mile pole, I thought I was in a great position
(with General Challenge),'' Pincay said. ''But there was no fire in
him then. I asked, but it wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   General Challenge came in as the favorite despite losing his
last two races. He lost to Early Pioneer by a length in the
Hollywood Gold Cup on July 9, following a 90-day layoff after
incurring a throat problem in an April race.
</P>
<P>
   Since last year's win in the Pacific Classic, General Challenge
had three victories in eight races.
</P>
<P>
   Ecton Park, who has only one win this year, was the only entry
from the East Coast in the field.
</P>
<P>
   In another mishap before the Pacific Classic, jockey Chris
McCarron was thrown by Mandola heading to the gate for the seventh
race. Mandola raced unattended around the track and was scratched.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
