<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nader Hails WTO Protesters  </HEADLINE>
By MIA PENTA
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Green Party presidential hopeful Ralph Nader said
Saturday that last fall's World Trade Organization protests were a
watershed in American history, and he hopes the same populist wave
responsible carries him to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ''The beautiful aspect of it is, it didn't end in Seattle,''
Nader told 300 people jammed into the Seattle Labor Temple. ''This
is an all-purpose social justice movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader was still exulting from the biggest event of his campaign.
On Friday night, 10,000 people paid $7 each to hear him at the
Memorial Coliseum in Portland, Ore. He said Democratic nominee Vice
President Al Gore and Republican nominee George W. Bush could not
have drawn that many people without help from big-money
contributors.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, he held a news conference and endorsed state
Insurance Commissioner Deborah Senn for U.S. Senate before visiting
the labor hall, where he told supporters the Democratic Party has
taken the labor movement's support for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Democratic Party cannot win an election nationally without
the labor vote,'' Nader said. But Democrats have ignored labor
because ''they think organized labor has nowhere else to go.''
</P>
<P>
   He called for a repeal of the federal Taft-Hartley Act, which he
said restricted the ability of workers to unionize.
</P>
<P>
   Nader saved most of his venom for Democrats because the
Republicans are so corrupted by big money that they hardly deserved
a mention, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he did take one stab at Bush, joking that Bush's candidacy
might be unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's nothing more than a giant corporation running for the
presidency, disguised as a person,'' Nader said.
</P>
<P>
   Nader promised to stand up for people forgotten by Democrats and
Republicans corrupted by big business. Any differences between
major-party stances on issues like abortion and environment are
more talk than substance, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The two conventions reflected (that) the two parties are
molding into one corporate party wearing two heads with different
makeup,'' Nader said.
</P>
<P>
   Nader, a longtime consumer crusader, has supporters among
environmentalists, labor and foes of the World Trade Organization.
If elected, he said he would end commercial logging in national
forests, and use what he characterized as taxpayer subsidies for
the timber industry to preserve and restore forests -- a move he
said would create more jobs than logging.
</P>
<P>
   He said he favors breaching the four Snake River dams to protect
dwindling salmon runs. Gore has ''waffled'' on the issue, he said,
and ''George W. Bush wouldn't even know where it is.''
</P>
<P>
   A Evans-McDonough telephone poll of 615 Washington state voters
last weekend showed Nader backed by 5 percent. Gore was backed by
44 percent, Bush by 42 percent, and Reform Party Pat Buchanan by 1
percent. The remaining 8 percent were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   The survey's margin of error was plus or minor 4 percentage
points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
