<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Lazio swap tax plan attacks  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   NYACK, N.Y. (AP) - U.S. Senate opponents Hillary Rodham Clinton
and Rick Lazio spent Saturday bashing each other's tax plans, with
the first lady condemning his proposal as ''risky'' and the
congressman blasting hers as bad for New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, on the campaign trail in Rockland County with her
mother, dismissed Lazio's plan as ''fiscally irresponsible ...
risky, irresponsible, imprudent.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The numbers don't add up,'' she said after addressing a
gathering of several hundred women on the 80th anniversary of
women's suffrage in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, in turn, defended his proposal while condemning the
Clinton plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mrs. Clinton doesn't trust New Yorkers and believes only
Washington bureaucrats know how to spend our hard-earned money,''
he said in a statement issued by his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a new Zogby poll, to be printed in the New York
Post's Sunday edition, showed the first lady drawing up to a
statistical dead heat with Lazio. The poll shows Clinton leading
Lazio 47 percent to 45 percent among the 601 likely voters polled
last week. The poll has a margin of error of 4.1 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio unveiled a sweeping $776 billion, 10-year tax-cut plan on
Thursday, aimed at countering proposals offered earlier by the
first lady. It was his first major policy proposal since announcing
his candidacy for U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   For several months, Clinton has touted her own program that
includes grants and targeted tax cuts to stimulate the economy,
particularly in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the Lazio plan ''is not going to give one penny to
paying down the national debt, or preserving Social Security, or
providing a prescription drug benefit for Medicare - all of which I
have advocated.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, noting that the current surplus is about $4.4 billion,
said his plan would return some of that money to ''the families
that built that surplus with their hard-earned tax dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   While in Lake Placid, to speak to a Kiwanis Club convention,
Lazio told reporters that he felt he had the edge over Clinton
because voters ''want someone who can work well with others and can
get the job done and can reflect their values. I think a lot of
people simply want to make a statement about trust and integrity
and I think this is their opportunity to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   In his brief speech to ''fellow Kiwanians'' Lazio noted that his
father and uncle were both leaders of Kiwanis clubs on Long Island
and that he was a member of the club in Lindenhurst that his father
helped found. Lazio didn't talk politics but only about the service
work that Kiwanis does.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, while Clinton campaigned in Rockland County, her
campaign manager appeared at Lazio's Manhattan headquarters with an
oversized calculator and a complaint: he said the congressman's tax
plan doesn't add up.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a story in the Daily News, one from the Washington Post,
and various studies by congress, Bill de Blasio said the cuts Lazio
wants would sap more than $1 trillion dollars from federal coffers
over 10 years. Lazio has put the cost at $776 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's obvious he needs some help doing the math,'' de Blasio
said. ''That huge difference needs to be explained to New
Yorkers.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio spokesman Dan McLagan said the discrepancies between their
numbers and Clinton's arise because the two sides are calculating
the costs of proposals that sound similar, but aren't.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're wrong and they know it,'' McLagan said of the Clinton
campaign assertions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
