<DOCNO> APW20000826.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani aide setting up fund-raising committee to help Lazio  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The head of New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's aborted U.S. Senate campaign against Hillary Rodham
Clinton is setting up a fund-raising committee to help the first
lady's new Republican challenger, Rep. Rick Lazio, a mayoral
adviser said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The adviser, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
independent committee being created by Bruce Teitelbaum was
expected to raise more than $2.5 million in the coming weeks, money
that could be used just before Election Day to pay for television
ads aimed at boosting Republican turnout in what is expected to be
a close race.
</P>
<P>
   The adviser said the committee, which has yet to be formally
established, has the support of Giuliani, who left the Senate race
in mid-May to battle prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is one of the ways we can be helpful,'' the Giuliani
adviser said.
</P>
<P>
   Under Teitelbaum's plans, the independent committee would raise
money by tapping into the mayor's Senate donor base. It contributed
more than $23 million to the mayor's Senate campaign. Contributions
to the new committee would come in the form of unlimited soft-money
donations. That means the money couldn't be used for ads that
directly advocate voting for Lazio, but could be used for ones that
seek to boost Republican turnout or that promote the congressman
from Long Island or attack the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have nothing to say about that,'' Teitelbaum, Giuliani's
Senate campaign manager, said Saturday when asked about the new
committee, first reported in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   A downside for Lazio is that he has been attacking Clinton for
her aggressive soft-money fund-raising activity. That means the
Lazio camp will likely keep its distance, at least publicly, from
the Teitelbaum effort.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio campaign spokesman Dan McLagan said Saturday that he knew
nothing about the Teitelbaum effort.
</P>
<P>
   Later, at an appearance in Lake Placid, where he attended his
second fund-raiser of the day and spoke to a Kiwanis convention,
Lazio said ''they have nothing to do with our campaign at all.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I can only say this, if Mrs. Clinton was willing to swear off
soft money - and they seem to be addicted to soft money, so I'm not
sure they're going to so this - I would be willing to tell all
outside groups, 'Thanks, but no thanks,' if she was willing to do
the same,'' the congressman added.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Giuliani has refunded about $2.8 million to donors to
his Senate campaign, accompanied by letters asking that the money
be sent on to Lazio. That is expected to be helpful to the
congressman because many of the donors who contributed to Giuliani
did so not so much because they supported him, but because they
wanted to block Clinton's election to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor still has more than $3 million in his campaign bank
account. Teitelbaum said Saturday that no decision has yet been
made about what to do with that money.
</P>
<P>
   As of the end of June, the Clinton campaign had collected almost
$19 million while Lazio had raised about $8.5 million for the race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-26-00 2134 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000826.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Little League WS Reaction  </HEADLINE>
By MARY LEE GRANT
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELLAIRE, Texas (AP) -- The boys of Bellaire are still hometown
heroes even though they lost the world championship on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Bellaire Little League All-Stars, called ''The Boys of
Summer,'' by their suburban Houston supporters, lost to Venezuela
3-2 in Williamsport, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   As the Venezuelan players fell upon each other in a celebratory
hug, Bellaire residents stood before a large screen TV in their
community center to cheer proudly for their defeated team.
</P>
<P>
   While die-hard fans watched the final inning, bored little girls
stood outside and whispered about crushes they had developed on the
players. Little boys ran around the community center creating bases
out of chairs, walls and tables dreaming of becoming the next Chuck
Knoblauch or Jose Cruz Jr., major leaguers who once played for
Bellaire High School.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers lounged at the back of the dark gym in lawn furniture
or stretched out on beach blankets. Some sat on bean bag baseballs,
unloaded from an old Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are so proud of them to have gone so far,'' said Mandy
Nathan, a Houston attorney. ''It is a real accomplishment for a
town as small as Bellaire.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents say their sense of community is a greater prize than
any baseball trophy. The boys have brought the town's closeness
into the national spotlight, but it existed long before the
12-year-olds made headlines.
</P>
<P>
   ''The community support was here before,'' resident Cathy Riggs
said. ''I think that is why they have gone this far.''
</P>
<P>
   This city of about 14,000, was long ago surrounded by its
behemoth neighbor Houston's southwestward expansion. That proximity
to Houston's main business centers caused Bellaire's property
values to skyrocket since the mid-1980s oil bust, yet the downtown
area still retains a small-town feel.
</P>
<P>
   Two-story Georgian-style houses dot the city, which proudly
proclaims its parks among the nation's safest, and posts photos of
its purple-suited swim team, the Bellaire Barracudas, in city
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Bellaire resident Herv Fisher said he is amazed at the team's
success.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are just little guys,'' Fisher said. ''A lot of them
aren't over 5 feet tall and they are skinny. And they have beaten
kids who are 6-foot-2 and weigh 230 pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Bellaire is no stranger to baseball glory. The city's high
school, part of the Houston school district, last year tied South
San Antonio's record of seven state championships.
</P>
<P>
   With its defeat, Bellaire failed to join the Houston National
All-Stars of 1950 and Westbury of 1966 as the only local teams to a
win a world title.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-26-00 2134 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000826.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 54-year-old doctor charged with murdering parents  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CHATHAM TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) - Police arrested a 54-year-old
Chatham Township woman for allegedly killing her elderly parents.
</P>
<P>
   Idella ''Kathleen'' Hagen reported the death of her parents to
police early Saturday morning, according to the Morris County
prosecutor's office. When officers arrived at the home, they found
the bodies of 86-year-old James Hagen and 92-year-old Idella F.
Hagen in separate beds in their bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities determined that the parents had been dead for
several days, the prosecutor's office said, and a medical examiner
indicated the bodies showed signs of asphyxiation.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested Hagen, who has lived with her parents since
July, and charged her with two counts of murder. The prosecutor's
office said Hagen is a licensed medical doctor who specialized in
urology. She did not establish a practice in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Hagen has been remanded to the Morris County Correctional
Facility in lieu of bail.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Christopher Linne says police are still investigating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-26-00 2136 </TRAILER>
