<DOCNO> APW20000826.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New poll shows Clinton and Lazio in statistical dead heat  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - A new poll shows that Hillary Rodham Clinton and
Rep. Rick Lazio are in a statistical dead heat among likely voters
in this year's Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also shows Vice President Al Gore with a commanding New
York state lead over Texas Gov. George W. Bush in the presidential
race.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, to be published in Sunday's edition of the New York
Post, was conducted by Zogby International for the Post and Fox 5
News.
</P>
<P>
   It shows the first lady leading Lazio 47 percent to 45 percent
among the 601 people who were polled on Thursday and Friday, with a
margin of error of 4.1 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Gore leads Bush by a solid 20 points, 54 percent to 34 percent,
the poll found.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the poll represent an improvement for Clinton in
recent weeks. A Zogby poll conducted for the Post last month showed
the first lady trailing Lazio 42 percent to 50 percent, with a four
percentage point error margin.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton campaign was pleased with the upswing in the first
lady's numbers, and anticipated that it would continue.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are confident that as New Yorkers continue to focus on the
differences between Hillary and her opponent, that gap will
continue to widen,'' said campaign spokeswoman Cathie Levine.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio was also positive about the results.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel great about that,'' he said of the poll. ''I just think
considering the post-convention bounce and the millions of dollars
in soft-money attack ads that have been aimed at me over the last
few weeks, to be where we are is good news for our campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio declined to speak at the Republican National Convention
and was not offered a prime-time slot by the Republicans. He spent
only one day at the convention. Clinton spent four days in Los
Angeles at the Democratic National Convention, and had a prime-time
speech on opening night.
</P>
<P>
   The new poll shows Clinton regaining ground among Jewish voters
after a decline last month. The poll has Clinton leading Lazio
among Jews, 55 percent to 33 percent, which is similar to her
showing in polls prior to last month. In last month's Zogby poll,
she had dropped to 48 percent, compared to his 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom holds that a Democratic Senate candidate
must capture at least 60 percent of the Jewish vote to win.
</P>
<P>
   The new poll also finds that Lazio continues to lead Clinton
upstate, 51 percent to 40 percent, and still holds a strong lead in
the suburbs with 55 percent support to Clinton's 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has 70 percent support in New York City and 96 percent
support among black voters, the poll said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite marked improvement in most categories of the poll,
Clinton is still viewed unfavorably by 45 percent of those polled,
compared to 31 percent for Lazio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-26-00 2137 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000826.0160 </DOCNO>
