<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spanish Hikers Killed in India  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Bandits with wooden truncheons
bludgeoned and killed a Spanish woman and her son trekking in a
lower Himalayan region in northern India and seriously wounded
their British friend, officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The unidentified attackers assaulted the Spaniards and threw
their bodies into a gorge Friday when they were camping in the
Parvati Valley, police said. The attack came in a remote and
thickly forested area famous for its sulphur springs, a police
spokesman in Kullu, the largest town in the region, told The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish news agency Efe identified the slain Spaniards as
Maria Angeles Girones, 34, and her son Cristobal, 14. The Spanish
foreign ministry said the two were apparently from Valencia.
</P>
<P>
   State police chief A.K. Puri identified the Briton as Martin
Young, Press Trust of India reported. The news agency said Young
was being treated at a hospital in the mountain resort of Kullu,
225 miles north of India's capital, New Delhi, in mountainous
Himachal Pradesh state.
</P>
<P>
   The police spokesman said the deserted valley where the trekkers
were attacked is a two-day trip from the nearest small town,
Manikaran. The trekkers had ventured alone into the remote area and
were not accompanied by porters or guides, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Few other details were immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   A German tourist was killed in the Hanta Pass area in the same
district last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-26-00 2214 </TRAILER>
