<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentine Man Held in Mexico  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A man accused of torturing political
prisoners during Argentina's military dictatorship can be held for
60 days while Spanish officials proceed with an extradition
request, a federal judge ruled Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Miguel Cavallo was being detained in a Mexico City
prison under the order from federal Judge Jesus Guadalupe Luna, the
federal attorney general's office said.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling came a day after police identified Cavallo as the man
accused of torturing people at the infamous Navy Mechanical School
in Argentina during the military dictatorship, which ended in 1983.
Spanish Judge Baltasar Garzon, who is investigating human rights
abuses under the former military dictatorships of Chile and
Argentina, has accused Cavallo of torture, terrorism, car theft and
forgery.
</P>
<P>
   At least 9,000 Argentines vanished during the country's
seven-year military dictatorship. Human rights groups put the
figure closer to 30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Cavallo's arrest came after five former political prisoners
identified him as their alleged torturer, Miguel Angel Cavallo.
Interpol said Cavallo used the name Miguel Angel while in the army.
</P>
<P>
   Cavallo has admitted to serving in Argentina's military but has
denied the charges against him. In Buenos Aires on Saturday,
mothers of people who disappeared during the dictatorship demanded
his extradition to Spain, local media reported.
</P>
<P>
   Cavallo had been serving as director of Mexico's private
National Registry of Motor Vehicles. After he was arrested, the
company announced his replacement and urged authorities to
investigate his identity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-26-00 2217 </TRAILER>
