<HEADLINE> Diamondbacks 5, Mets 1, 10 Innings  </HEADLINE>
By IRA PODELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Luis Gonzalez's RBI double sparked a four-run
10th inning against Rick White as the Arizona Diamondbacks beat the
New York Mets 5-1 Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona cut San Francisco's lead in the NL West to 2&AMP;frac12; games and
the Mets' wild card advantage to 4&AMP;frac12;. The Diamondbacks snapped their
six-game losing streak at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Bell hit a ground-rule double to left with one out in the
10th off White (2-1) before Gonzalez sent a shot over the head of
center fielder Jay Payton.
</P>
<P>
   After Matt Williams lined out, Steve Finley was walked
intentionally. Greg Colbrunn followed with a double that scored
Gonzalez and Finley to make it 4-1. Damian Miller singled in
Colbrunn to finish the scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Plesac (3-0) pitched a perfect ninth for the victory. Matt
Mantei got the final three outs in a non-save situation.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza, who absorbed a thunderous blow from Bell in a home
plate collision in the fourth, hit Brian Anderson's 1-2 pitch two
innings later into the left-center field bleachers for his 33rd
homer of the season to make it 1-0. He had three of the Mets' five
hits and Mike Bordick had the other two.
</P>
<P>
   Bell opened the fourth with a triple off the base of the
center-field fence. Gonzalez followed with a fly to medium-center
that Payton caught.
</P>
<P>
   Payton fired a one-hop strike into Piazza's glove as Bell
charged in. Bell struck Piazza in the face with his right forearm,
sending the catcher backward still in possession of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The fans chanted ''MVP! MVP!'' as Piazza was attended to by the
trainer and manager Bobby Valentine.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona made it 1-all in the seventh on David Dellucci's
pinch-hit RBI single. With two outs, Miller doubled, Danny Bautista
walked and Dellucci hit a soft liner to center.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby J. Jones and Anderson were locked in a duel until Piazza's
sixth-inning homer. Dellucci batted for Anderson, who worked six
innings and allowed one run on four hits. Jones, in seven innings,
allowed one run and seven hits.
Notes: Mets LF Benny Agbayani flied out to center, leading off the
first, to snap his streak of reaching base in 10 straight plate
appearances. ... Anderson, the NL leader with a 1.5 walks per nine
inning ratio, issued his only two bases on balls in the fourth. ...
Jones is 0-for-33 at the plate this season. ... Williams has not
driven in a run in 34 at-bats.
</P>
</TEXT>
