<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Men Convicted in Brazil Massacre  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Two squatters were convicted of
manslaughter Saturday for the deaths of two policemen in one of
Brazil's bloodiest land disputes, local media reported.
</P>
<P>
   A judge in Porto Velho, capital of the Amazon state of Rondonia,
sentenced Claudenir Gilberto Ramos to eight years in prison and
Cicero Pereira Leite to six years after the men were found guilty
by a seven-member jury, the Estado News Agency reported. Both are
free pending appeal, the agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courthouse, 200 demonstrators, including church and
union leaders, protested the politically charged decision, which
they said was unfair. They were ringed by police in riot gear.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths occurred during a 1995 incident: 300 police stormed a
squatters' camp, tossing tear gas and firing wildly in the southern
Amazon town of Corumbiara, 1,800 miles northwest of Rio de Janeiro.
The clash left the two police officers and 10 squatters dead.
</P>
<P>
   Autopsy reports later showed that of the 10 squatters killed,
seven were shot point blank in the face, neck, chest and back. One
victim was shot 19 times. Another was shot 12 times in the face.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the police argued they were met with gunfire as they
arrived to carry out an eviction order.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the two squatters, 13 police officers are being
tried in connection to the massacre.
</P>
<P>
   In a trial a week ago, two officers were sentenced to 16 years
and 18 years for murder for their role in the massacre, while a
third was acquitted. In a second trial, two officers were
acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   In the case that ended Saturday, there was no direct evidence
linking Leite or Ramos to the shots that killed the two officers.
But prosecutors argued that the two organized armed groups within
the squatter camp to resist police raids.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters contend that there was less evidence against the
two squatters than against the police who were acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   Unequal land distribution is at the root of rural violence in
Brazil, where 90 percent of the land belongs to 20 percent of the
people and the poorest 40 percent own just 1 percent of the land.
Over the past decade more than 1,000 people have lost their lives
in land disputes here, according to the Land Pastoral, a Catholic
group that advocates land reform.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-26-00 2235 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000826.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ingrassia Wins Yonkers Trot  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   YONKERS, N.Y. (AP) -- Jacqueline Ingrassia guided Goalfish
through the stretch to overtake Approved Action and become the
first female driver to win the Yonkers Trot, the second leg of the
Triple Crown, at Yonkers Raceway on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Goalfish caught Approved Action, who took the lead at the
three-quarter mile pole midway through the stretch to win by a head
in 1:59.
</P>
<P>
   Approved Action, the favorite with Rejean Daigneault driving,
was outside for the entire race until going on top in 1:28.9 at the
three-quarter pole. But Goalfish wore him down in the stretch.
Brumal Hanover, with Ron Pierce, was third.
</P>
<P>
   ''I fell in early and took a shot at Approved Action,'' said
Ingrassia, who is 3-1-0 in 11 starts with the 3-year-old bay colt.
''It paid off.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was a dream come true made possible by his perfect
trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Goalfish, who did not race as a 2-year-old, earned $172,702 for
the victory to boost his winnings to $202,511.
</P>
<P>
   The winner returned $28.20, $10.20 and $4.70. Approved Action
paid $3.30 and $2.60 and Brumal Hanover $2.40.
</P>
<P>
   Goalfish, trained by Ingrassia's husband, Frank, is not entered
in the Kentucky Futurity, the third leg of the Triple Crown, on
Oct. 9 in Lexington, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   ''My husband and I are just good horse people and we work hard
at what we do,'' Jacqueline Ingrassia said. ''There is a
possibility that we will supplement him into the Kentucky Futurity.
We should know in a day or two.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be no Triple Crown winner because Yankee Paco, winner
of the Hambletonian, opted to race in the American National at
Balmoral in Crete, Ill., on Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
