Associated Press.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Praises Nigeria's President
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ABUJA, Nigeria (AP) -- Calling Nigeria ''a pivot point on which all Africa's
future turns,'' President Clinton appealed to the leaders of this oil-rich
nation Saturday to set aside political acrimony so that their citizens can lift
themselves from poverty and isolation. Standing in the cavernous National
Assembly chamber Clinton praised President Olusegun Obasanjo's leadership in
stabilizing Nigeria. One of Clinton's purposes in coming was to encourage a
tender democracy to take root here in Africa's most populous nation.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Combined Fires Gain Western Ground
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HELENA, Mont. (AP) -- Wildfires have burned together in southwestern
Montana's Bitterroot Valley and along the Continental Divide, forming the
nation's largest fire group, a federal official said today. And elsewhere in the
West, potential evacuation plans were ready for two small towns threatened by a
blaze in Washington. The Bitterroot Valley fire and the Mussigbrod fires in the
Big Hole River drainage covered an estimated 247,000 acres, said E. Lynn Burkett
of the National Interagency Fire Center in Boise, Idaho.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nader Hails WTO Protests
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Green Party presidential hopeful Ralph Nader said today that
last fall's World Trade Organization protests were a watershed in American
history, and he hopes the same populist wave responsible carries him to the
White House. ''The beautiful aspect of it is, it didn't end in Seattle,'' Nader
told 300 people jammed into the Seattle Labor Temple. ''This is an all-purpose
social justice movement.'' Nader also endorsed state Insurance Commissioner
Deborah Senn for U.S. Senate before visiting the labor hall, where he told
supporters the Democratic Party has taken the labor movement's support for
granted.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Argentine Man Held in Mexico
</SUBHEAD>
