<HEADLINE> Notes from Saturday's Baseball Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Devil Rays-Orioles:
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: Tanyon Sturtze pitched two innings Saturday before
leaving with a strained oblique muscle. He expects to miss at least
two starts. ... Dave Eiland made his first relief appearance since
April 18. He has been scratched from his scheduled start Tuesday
against Boston. ... Fred McGriff's homer off Sidney Ponson was his
first off a right-hander since July 7.
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE: Sidney Ponson gave up two homers Saturday and has
yielded 26 in 26 starts this season. ... The Orioles have 10
complete games, second in the AL behind Toronto (12). ... Mike
Kinkade made his first start in the majors in the nightcap. He
batted seventh and played DH.
Blue Jays-Rangers:
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: With eight shutout innings against Texas on Friday
night, he has pitched at least eight innings in 11 of his 28
starts. ... Toronto is 15-19 against left-handed starters.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: With Friday night's 1-0 victory over the Blue Jays, the
Rangers are 45-37 all-time in 1-0 games. The team's last 1-0 win
came against Oakland on July 10, 1998.
Red Sox-Royals:
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: SS Nomar Garciaparra started Saturday night after
missing three games with a strained left hamstring. ... The game
started at 8:05 p.m. CDT, an hour later than usual, because of the
Eddie Robinson Classic college football game between Iowa and
Kansas State at adjacent Arrowhead Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: Mike Sweeney, who entered the game with 115 RBIs,
is on pace for a club-record 146. Hal McRae owns the record with
133 in 1982.
Tigers-Twins:
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: Dave Mlicki, 4-10 this season with Detroit, will make a
rehabilitation start Sunday for West Michigan of the Class A
Midwest League. He has been on the DL since July 23 with severe
sinus infection that required surgery. ... The Tigers are
guaranteed a winning record for August. That gave Detroit three
straight winning months for the first time since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: The Twins may be looking for a Triple-A affiliate in
2001. Salt Lake City, the Twins' affiliate in the Pacific Coast
League for the past seven years, has filed a notice with the
National Association indicating the team is interested in getting a
new affiliation. The list of teams seeking new affiliations will be
available publicly Monday. Minnesota's relationship with Buzz owner
Joe Buzas goes back to 1986. At the time, Buzas owned the team in
Portland, moving to Salt Lake City in 1994.
Yankees-Athletics:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: Jose Canseco started Saturday's game in left field,
the first time he's been in the outfield since July 9, 1999, at
Florida as a member of the Tampa Bay Devil Rays. He made six starts
in left field last year. Glenallen Hill was originally scheduled to
start in the outfield, but switched with Canseco when he didn't
feel comfortable. ... David Justice was given the day off to rest
his sore neck. ... 2B Chuck Knoblauch will miss a day or two on his
minor league rehab assignment after getting hit near his left knee
in a Class A game on Friday. ''He just has a bruise,'' manager Joe
Torre said. ''We're going to move him to Columbus so he can see
Triple-A pitching. That will help him get back here faster.'' ...
Former Yankees and A's great Reggie Jackson was a visitor to the
New York clubhouse before the game. ... OF Paul O'Neill was given
an additional day off to rest his sore hip with the Yankees facing
a left-hander. He and Justice are expected to play Sunday. ... OF
Bernie Williams was back in center field for the first time since
Aug. 18, but will likely sit on Sunday, though he said he was
willing to bat right-handed against a right-handed pitcher to help
take the pressure off his sore rib cage. He's hit right-handed
against knuckleballer Tim Wakefield, but never on a consistent
basis against righties ''probably since rookie ball. I'm very
encouraged,'' said Williams. ''When I first hurt it, I thought I'd
be out a month. But when I hit off the tee, I didn't feel any
pain.'' ... Infielder D'Angelo Jimenez was reinstated from the
60-day disabled list and optioned to Triple-A Columbus, where he
has been on a rehab assignment. ... RHP Ramiro Mendoza, on the
disabled list with tendinitis in his right shoulder, threw in the
outfield with Tampa on Saturday. The Yankees are hopeful he might
throw off a mound by early September.
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: Manager Art Howe was surprised when informed 1B Jason
Giambi said he wouldn't be able to play in the field the rest of
the year on Friday. ''That's news to me,'' Howe said. ''I haven't
talked to him about that. We'll just wait and see.'' Howe said he
hasn't even talked to team trainers about when Giambi could
possibly return to the field. For his part, Giambi said he would
reassess the situation in two weeks. ''I've had injuries all year.
It's part of the game,'' said Giambi. ''You learn to suck it up and
play.'' ... Former A's star Jose Canseco, now with the Yankees,
said he's impressed by his former club this year. ''They have a lot
of ability and they're winning games tooth and nail,'' said
Canseco, who broke into the majors with the A's in 1985 and spent
parts of nine seasons in two different stints in Oakland. ... The
playing conditions were still poor at Oakland Coliseum two days
after the Oakland Raiders played an exhibition game there. ''The
outfield is very bumpy,'' said Howe. ''It's like a billiards
table.''
White Sox-Mariners:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: The White Sox moved back James Baldwin (13-5, 4.29),
who was scheduled to start Sunday, until Tuesday night in Oakland.
He missed his last scheduled start last Wednesday night against
Baltimore because of a tired arm. His 13 victories this season
match his career best set in 1998. ... In Baldwin's place, Sean
Lowe (3-1) will pitch for the White Sox on Sunday. ... In Jose
Valentin's career-high 13-game hitting streak, he was 20-for-54
(.370) with six doubles, a triple, two home runs, 12 RBIs and 16
runs scored. ... With their 76-52 record, the White Sox were off to
their best 128-game start since the 1964 White Sox began at 77-51.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: 3B Carlos Guillen was back in the starting lineup
Saturday night after being replaced by David Bell a day earlier.
Guillen's 14 errors in 63 games lead the Mariners. ... DH Edgar
Martinez is hitting .351 (120-for-342) in 99 games at Safeco Field
compared to his average in the Kingdome of .321 (710-for-2,212).
Indians-Angels:
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: RHP Charles Nagy is scheduled to start his second
