Angels debut.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Dodgers-Cubs:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: OF Devon White's pulled quad isn't as bad as first
thought. After originally saying White would be out at least a
week, manager Davey Johnson said Saturday that White will probably
miss only half that time. ''It did pop, but it's not as bad as I
thought it was,'' said White, who kept ice on his leg for most of
Friday night. White blamed the injury on his lack of playing time
this season. After playing in 100 or more games eight of the last
nine years, he's only played 45 games this season. ''It's tough
when your body is used to being in there every day. Then you're
not, that's what happens,'' he said. ... Closer Jeff Shaw saved
both games of Friday's doubleheader, giving him 20 for the season.
He's saved 20 or more in three straight seasons, only the third
Dodger reliever to do so. ... The Dodgers sweep of Friday's
doubleheader was their first since beating the Montreal Expos twice
on July 6, 1992.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: On Aug. 26, 1939, the Cubs and Braves played a
doubleheader in the first televised major league baseball game. Fox
Sports, which broadcast Saturday's game, used the anniversary to
take a look back at how broadcasting has changed through the years,
starting the game in black-and-white. Breaks between innings were
extended to three minutes to accommodate the broadcast. While that
made for a long day for the players, Cubs manager Don Baylor took
it in stride. ''Believe it or not, we work for television,'' he
said. ''It's an entertainment business and we have to look at it
like that.'' ... Rick Aguilera has converted his last nine save
opportunities.
Astros-Expos:
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: C Tony Eusebio has raised his average from .203 to .271
over the course of his career-high 21-game hitting streak. Eusebio
was 29-for-76 (.382) over the course of the streak entering
Saturday night's game. Art Howe hit in 23 consecutive games in 1981
to set the Astros' team record, which was tied by Luis Gonzalez in
1997. ... Jeff Bagwell has 30 RBIs in August and needs one more to
tie the team record for most in one month. Bagwell and Derek Bell
set the record with 31 RBIs in July 1995 and Bagwell tied it with
31 in May 1996.
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: Vladimir Guerrero started in right field for the first
time since last Monday in Los Angeles. Guerrero missed four starts
with a strained left shoulder. ... The Expos have lost nine
straight at Olympic Stadium and four straight overall. The team
record for consecutive home losses is 12, set by the first edition
of the Expos which lost 12 straight at Jarry Park from May 13-June
24, 1969.
