<HEADLINE> Naval Officer Dies of Cancer  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- James L. George, 60, a retired Navy officer
and writer who was an authority on natural security affairs, died
of cancer Aug. 24 at his home in nearby Potomac, Md.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote extensively on naval issues and was the author of
''History of Warships,'' published in 1998, and ''U.S. Navy in the
1990s: Alternatives for Action,'' published in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   He also was the U.S. contributing editor of U.S. Naval Forces,
published in Germany, and a commentary writer for Defense News,
Navy Times and other publications covering the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   He worked a staffer for House and Senate committees,
specializing in national security issues, and served in the Reagan
administration as assistant director for multilateral affairs at
the Arms Control and Disarmament Agency.
</P>
</TEXT>
