<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police investigate triple homicide, suicide  </HEADLINE>
By STEVE FEICA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERBURY, Conn. (AP) - A 29-year-old city man went on a killing
rampage Saturday, gunning down a neighbor, a city firefighter and
the mother of an ex-girlfriend before killing himself, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Although authorities said they had no one clear motive early in
their investigation, they said the gunmen knew all three victims.
He was in an ongoing dispute with his neighbor, and may have shot
his ex-girlfriend's mother to get back at the girlfriend for
breaking off their relationship, police said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It almost appears like it's three separate shootings for three
different reasons,'' said Waterbury Police Superintendent Edward
Flaherty.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting spree began just before 11 a.m. when Mark Cote, got
into an argument with Brian Miller, 30, who lived on the third
floor of the same multiple family home where Cote lived, police
said. Police said Cote and Miller had an ongoing neighbor dispute,
but would not say what they had been arguing about.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Joe Pesce said Cote may have ''snapped'' in the argument
with Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Flaherty said Cote shot Miller as his neighbor sat in his car,
dragged him out and shot him again before fleeing the scene in
Miller's car.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Cote had two weapons, a .25-caliber semiautomatic
handgun and a Tech 9-type automatic pistol.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after shooting Miller, police said Cote drove a few
miles to the intersection of Highland Avenue and Sunnyside Avenue
where four city firefighters were collecting money from motorists
for the ''Fill The Boot'' campaign for Muscular Dystrophy.
</P>
<P>
   Cote shot and killed Jamie Quinones, 38, a city firefighter who
had been with the department for six years, then fled.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 15 minutes after Quinones was gunned down, police
received a 911 call from a home on Kenyon St., but the phone was
quickly hung up. The 911 operator called back and was told by the
man who answered that everyone was O.K. and ''one of the kids must
have been playing with the phone.''
</P>
<P>
   The 911 operator called a second time and Maria Perez, 23,
answered, saying that her ex-boyfriend, Cote, had shot and killed
her mother. Perez broke off her relationship with Cote two weeks
ago, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police responded to the home and found Miller's car in front
with the engine still running. When police arrived, Perez ran from
the home with her three children and told officers that Cote shot
her mother on the first floor and was now on the second floor of
the house with a gun.
</P>
<P>
   It was at that point that police heard a shot from within the
house, closed off the area and called in the Waterbury Emergency
Response team.
</P>
<P>
   Several attempts were made to contact Cote inside the house by
phone and with a bullhorn, but there was no response, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Officers then entered the house and found Cote dead from a
self-inflicted gunshot wound on the second floor. They found the
body of Maria Hernandez, 40, on the first floor.
</P>
<P>
   Cote's mother said her son did not have a history of violence,
and gave no hints that something was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was perfectly fine this morning...he was on the phone, he
was fine,'' Rachel Cote said. ''He left and then everything
unfolded in the next hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Acting Fire Chief James Trainor described Quinones as ''a nice
guy, kind of quiet, with a military bearing.'' Quinones had spent
11 years in the Marines before become a city firefighter, he said.
</P>
<P>
   By late afternoon firefighters at the Highland Avenue firehouse,
less than a mile from where Quinones was killed, had place black
bunting outside the firehouse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-26-00 2334 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000826.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man Kills 3, Self in Connecticut  </HEADLINE>
By STEVE FEICA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERBURY, Conn. (AP) -- A man went on a killing spree Saturday,
gunning down three people, including a firefighter who was
collecting money for charity, before shooting himself to death,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   The gunman knew all three victims but authorities hadn't
determined why he targeted them. One victim was a neighbor and
another was the mother of an ex-girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ''It almost appears like it's three separate shootings for three
different reasons,'' said Police Superintendent Edward Flaherty.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting spree began when the suspect, identified as Mark
Cote, 29, got into an argument with Brian Miller, 30, who lived in
the same multiple family home as Cote, police said. The two had an
ongoing dispute, but police would not say why they were arguing
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Flaherty said Cote shot Miller while his neighbor was sitting in
his car, dragged him out and shot him again before fleeing in the
car.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Cote had two weapons, a .25-caliber semiautomatic
handgun and a Tech 9-type automatic pistol.
</P>
<P>
   After shooting Miller, police said Cote drove a few miles to an
intersection where four firefighters were collecting money from
motorists for the Muscular Dystrophy Association. Cote shot and
killed firefighter Jamie Quinones, 38, then fled, police said.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 minutes later, Maria Perez, 23, told an emergency
dispatcher that Cote had shot and killed her mother. Perez broke
off her relationship with Cote two weeks ago, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrived at the house and heard a gunshot. They found Cote
dead from a self-inflicted gunshot wound on the second floor. The
body of Maria Hernandez, 40, was found on the first floor.
</P>
<P>
   Cote's mother said her son did not have a history of violence,
and gave no hints that something was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was perfectly fine this morning ... he was on the phone, he
was fine,'' Rachel Cote said. ''He left and then everything
unfolded in the next hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Waterbury is about 25 miles southwest of Hartford.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-26-00 2339 </TRAILER>
