<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-26 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Minn. Football Coach Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Cal Stoll, the former Minnesota football
coach who had a heart transplant 13 years ago, died Friday at
Fairview-University Hospital, a hospital spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Stoll, who was 74, had been ill for more than a month as heart
trouble caused damage to other vital organs. He died around 5 p.m.
Friday, the spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Stoll was 39-39 at Minnesota from 1972-78. He coached
quarterback Tony Dungy, now the head coach of the NFL's Tampa Bay
Buccaneers.
</P>
<P>
   Stoll's biggest win came in 1977, when the Gophers beat
top-ranked Michigan 16-0. Minnesota went on to compete in the Hall
of Fame Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Stoll was 15-17 at Wake Forest from 1969-71.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
